# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/2020-united-states-census] The **2020 United States census** was the 24th decennial United States census.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/2020-united-states-census] Census Day, the reference day used for the census, was April 1, 2020.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/2020-united-states-census] Other than a pilot study during the 2000 census, this was the first U.S. census to offer options to respond online or by phone, in addition to the paper response form used for previous censuses.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/2020-united-states-census] The census was taken during the COVID-19 pandemic, which affected its administration.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/2020-united-states-census] The census recorded a resident population of 331,449,281 in the 50 states and the national capital of Washington, D.C., reflecting an increase of 7.4%, or 22,703,743, over 2010.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/2020-united-states-census] The growth rate was the second-lowest ever recorded, and the net increase was the sixth-highest in history.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/2020-united-states-census] This was the first census where the ten most-populous states each surpassed ten million residents, and the first census where the ten most-populous cities each surpassed one million residents.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/2020-united-states-census] This census's data determined the electoral votes' distribution for the 2024 United States presidential election.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/2020-united-states-census] As required by the United States Constitution, the U.S. census has been conducted every 10 years since 1790.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/2020-united-states-census] The 2010 United States census was the previous census completed.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/2020-united-states-census] 18 and older are legally obligated to answer census questions, and to do so truthfully (Title 13 of the United States Code).
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/2020-united-states-census] Personally identifiable information is private and the Census Bureau itself will never release it.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/2020-united-states-census] However, the National Archives and Records Administration could release the original census returns in 2092, if the 72-year rule is not changed before then.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/2020-united-states-census] On census reference day, April 1, 2020, the resident United States population (50 states and Washington, D.C., excluding overseas territories and military members and civilian U.S. citizens living abroad) was projected to be 329.59 million, a 6.76% increase from the 2010 census.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/2020-united-states-census] The results of the 2020 census determine the number of seats for each state in the House of Representatives, hence also the number of electors for each state in the Electoral College, for elections from 2022 to 2032.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/2020-united-states-census] The Census Bureau announced the apportionment figures on April 26, 2021.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/2020-united-states-census] This represented a smaller number of seats shifting than was forecast by independent analysts.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/2020-united-states-census] State and local officials use censuses to redraw boundaries for districts such as congressional districts (redistricting), state legislative districts, and school districts.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/2020-united-states-census] Dozens of federal programs use census data to help direct funding to state and local areas.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/2020-united-states-census] Census results help determine how more than $675 billion in federal funding are allocated to states and communities each year for roads, schools, hospitals (health clinics), emergency services, and more.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/2020-united-states-census] The 2020 census was the first U.S. census to offer a full internet response option and the first to extensively use technology instead of paper to manage and conduct fieldwork.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/2020-united-states-census] Census Bureau submitted a list of questions to Congress on March 29, 2018.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/2020-united-states-census] The U.S. census will not share any participant's information with any government agency, as it is prohibited by Title 13 United States code.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/2020-united-states-census] It has been challenged, but the Supreme Court has always prevailed in reference to Title 13 to protect the confidentiality and privacy of information provided.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/2020-united-states-census] Used to produce statistics about homeownership and renters for economic indicators, housing programs and informing planning decisions.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/2020-united-states-census] The sex of each person in the household.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/2020-united-states-census] Used to produce statistics used to plan and fund government programs, enforce laws, regulations, and policies against discrimination.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/2020-united-states-census] The age of each person in the household.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/2020-united-states-census] Used to better understand the size and characteristics of different age groups.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/2020-united-states-census] Agencies use these data to plan and fund government programs that support specific age groups, including children and older populations.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/2020-united-states-census] The race of each person in the household.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/2020-united-states-census] Used by federal agencies to monitor compliance with anti-discrimination provisions, such as those under the Voting Rights Act and the Civil Rights Act.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/2020-united-states-census] Whether a person in the household is of Hispanic, Latino, or Spanish origin.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/2020-united-states-census] The relationship of each person in the household to each other.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/2020-united-states-census] Used to plan and fund government programs that support families, including people raising children alone and other households who qualify for additional assistance.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/2020-united-states-census] The United States Census Bureau proposed but then withdrew plans to add a new category to classify Middle Eastern and North African peoples, over a dispute over whether this classification should be considered a white ethnicity or a separate race.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/2020-united-states-census] According to the Census Bureau, 60.0% of all U.S. households had submitted their census questionnaire by May 22, 2020 –either online, by mail or by phone.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/2020-united-states-census] Most U.S. households were mailed an invitation letter between March 12–20 to self-respond.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/2020-united-states-census] They account for more than 95% of all U.S. households.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/2020-united-states-census] Prior to the ongoing coronavirus pandemic, the remaining 5% of U.S. households (mostly in rural areas) were supposed to be visited by census takers in April/May, dropping off invitation letters to owners.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/2020-united-states-census] This was delayed, but most census offices restarted work again in mid-May.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/2020-united-states-census] In an update published October 19, 2020, the Census Bureau stated 99.98% of addresses had been accounted for, with all but one state over a 99.9% rate.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/2020-united-states-census] Paper responses postmarked on or before October 15 would be processed, as long as they arrived at the processing center by October 22.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/2020-united-states-census] As in previous censuses, the 2020 census relied on a network of trusted voices nationwide to help raise awareness, answer questions, and encourage communities to participate.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/2020-united-states-census] Hundreds of local "complete count committees" are dedicating resources to the efforts nationwide.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/2020-united-states-census] VMLY&R (formerly Young & Rubicam) secured the Integrated Communications Contract for the 2020 census campaign in August 2016.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/2020-united-states-census] As the contract's primary agency of record, VMLY&R created an integrated team for this project, Team Y&R, which includes subcontractors specializing in minority outreach, digital media, earned media and more.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/2020-united-states-census] In March 2019, the campaign unveiled the 2020 census tagline: "Shape your future.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/2020-united-states-census] START HERE." The tagline was based on research that demonstrated which types of messages will reach and motivate all populations, including segments of the population who are historically hard to count.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/2020-united-states-census] The printing company Cenveo won the $61 million contract in October 2017 to produce census forms and reminders but went bankrupt less than four months later.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/2020-united-states-census] Government Publishing Office said the agency failed to check the company's financial status and improperly allowed the company to lower its bid after other bids were unsealed.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/2020-united-states-census] The coronavirus pandemic caused delays to census field operations and counts of the homeless and people living in group quarters.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/2020-united-states-census] As of April 1, 2020, Census Day, the Census Bureau still planned to complete the count by the end of the year.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/2020-united-states-census] Census Bureau issued a press release by Director Steven Dillingham announcing that 2020 census field operations would be suspended for two weeks until April 1, 2020, due to the COVID-19 pandemic.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/2020-united-states-census] On March 27, 2020, the agency announced it would temporarily suspend in-person interviews for its on-going surveys.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/2020-united-states-census] The agency claimed that staffing adjustments at its call centers due to implementing health guidance had "led to increases in call wait times, affecting different languages at different times".
