[src:adams-run-south-carolina/2020-united-states-census] Virgin Islands in preparation for resuming operations for the 2020 Island Areas Censuses" on May 22, 2020.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/2020-united-states-census] On May 29, 2020, a press release was published announcing "restart" of operations in seven additional states and the Washington, D.C., area starting from the week of June 1.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/2020-united-states-census] In a June 5, 2020, press release, the U.S.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/2020-united-states-census] Days later, the Navajo Nation began reinstating lockdown restrictions and curfews due to a surge in new cases.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/2020-united-states-census] A June 12, 2020, press release shared that the update leave (UL) operation had resumed, as well as fingerprinting of selected applicants.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/2020-united-states-census] On August 3, 2020, the Census Bureau announced that field collection would end on September 30, rather than October 31 as planned in April.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/2020-united-states-census] Zabarsky, Principal Assistant Inspector General for Audit and Evaluation published an alert on behalf of the Department of Commerce Office of Inspector General, which stated that the number of COVID-19 related safety issues raised by hotline complaints tripled between July 1 and August 21.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/2020-united-states-census] The U.S. decennial census is used to determine federal funds, grants, and support to states.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/2020-united-states-census] The Census Bureau had included a citizenship question until 1950 when it was removed, though it continued to include a question asking about place of birth.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/2020-united-states-census] Ross was accused by Democrats in Congress of lying that the citizenship question was requested by the Justice Department and approved by him.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/2020-united-states-census] Upon the bureau's announcement, several state and city officials criticized the decision, reiterating the concern about discouraging participation from immigrants, resulting in undercounting, and questioning the motives of Secretary Ross in adding the question.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/2020-united-states-census] Three simultaneous separate federal lawsuits came out of this discovery, occurring at the district courts of New York, Maryland, and California.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/2020-united-states-census] During these trials, documents released in May 2019 showed that the late Thomas B.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/2020-united-states-census] Hofeller, an architect of Republican gerrymandering, had found that adding the census question could help to gerrymander maps that "would be advantageous to Republicans and non-Hispanic whites".
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/2020-united-states-census] Hofeller later wrote the DOJ letter which justified the policy by claiming it was needed to enforce the 1965 Voting Rights Act.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/2020-united-states-census] The Trump administration on June 12, 2019, asserted executive privilege over portions of the requested documents.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/2020-united-states-census] As a result, the House committee subsequently voted along party lines to hold both Ross and Barr in contempt that day.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/2020-united-states-census] The full House voted to hold Ross and Barr in contempt on July 17, 2019, in a 230–198 vote along party lines.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/2020-united-states-census] A lawsuit, led by New York state's attorney general Barbara Underwood and joined by seventeen other states, fifteen cities and other civil rights groups, was filed in the United States District Court for the Southern District of New York.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/2020-united-states-census] During the discovery phase of the trial, new information came to light that Ross had had previous discussions with Steve Bannon before March 2018 with the intent to add the citizenship question, contradicting statements he had made to Congress in March.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/2020-united-states-census] Furman in September 2018 to ask that Ross clear a day in his schedule to give a deposition to the court related to the addition of the census question prior to the planned start of the trial in November.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/2020-united-states-census] The Trump administration filed a writ of *mandamus* to the United States Supreme Court, requesting that they postpone the trial, and also to defer any involvement with Ross until the start of the trial.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/2020-united-states-census] The Supreme Court issued an order that allowed the trial *United States Census Bureau v.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/2020-united-states-census] State of New York* to go forward, but agreed to postpone Ross's deposition until after the start of the trial.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/2020-united-states-census] The Supreme Court accepted the petition related to Furman's ruling on February 15, 2019, a separate matter from the question of Ross's deposition, and the case's oral arguments were heard on April 23, 2019.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/2020-united-states-census] The Supreme Court issued its decision on June 27, 2019, rejecting the Trump administration's stated rationale for including the question.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/2020-united-states-census] While the Court majority agreed that the question was allowable under the Enumeration Act, they also agreed with the ability of the District Court to ask Commerce for further explanation for the question under the Administrative Procedure Act (APA).
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/2020-united-states-census] They also agreed that the answers Commerce had provided at the time appeared to be "contrived" and pretextual, leaving open the possibility that Commerce could offer a better rationale.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/2020-united-states-census] The case was remanded back to the District Court, to allow Commerce to provide a better explanation for the rationale of the question to the District Court, who would deem if that was sufficient before allowing the question on the census.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/2020-united-states-census] The question would be allowed on the census only if these steps can be completed before the self-imposed form printing deadline.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/2020-united-states-census] The American Civil Liberties Union (ACLU) has taken steps to introduce the Hofeller evidence into the New York case but it will not be heard until late 2019 after the census forms are to be published.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/2020-united-states-census] The second suit over the census question came in the United States District Court for the Northern District of California under Judge Richard Seeborg, raised by the state of California and several cities within it.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/2020-united-states-census] In March 2019, Seeborg similarly found as Furman had in New York that the addition of the census question was unconstitutional and issued an injunction to block its use.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/2020-united-states-census] The government appealed to the Ninth Circuit before the Supreme Court remanded the case.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/2020-united-states-census] A similar question related to the intent of the question was raised by several immigrants-rights groups in the United States District Court for the District of Maryland.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/2020-united-states-census] The case was overseen by Judge George J.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/2020-united-states-census] Hazel had found for the pro-immigration groups in April 2019, ruling that the addition of an immigration question to the census was unconstitutional.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/2020-united-states-census] The government issued its appeal to the Fourth Circuit Court of Appeals.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/2020-united-states-census] The new Hofeller evidence was presented to Hazel as the case was being heard on appeal during June 2019 at the Fourth Circuit.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/2020-united-states-census] Hazel said the new evidence "raises a substantial issue".
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/2020-united-states-census] On June 25, 2019, the Fourth Circuit remanded the case back to Hazel's District Court with the newly provided evidence, and to review if the additional evidence showed discriminatory intent.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/2020-united-states-census] Should Hazel find such intent, it would be possible for him to place an injunction on the addition of the census question during a new discovery phase, regardless of the Supreme Court decision in *Department of Commerce v.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/2020-united-states-census] This action would effectively render the question moot since the census forms would need to be published at this point without the citizenship question to meet the mailing deadlines.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/2020-united-states-census] President Trump, after the Supreme Court decision in *Department of Commerce* was announced, stated his intent to find a way to delay the census as long as possible so the judicial matter could be resolved.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/2020-united-states-census] On July 2, 2019, the Department of Justice (DOJ) announced that the citizenship question would not be included in the census, and the Commerce Department began printing census forms without a citizenship question.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/2020-united-states-census] However, the next day, Trump insisted his administration was "absolutely moving forward" with the citizenship question, and the Justice Department confirmed in court that it had been instructed to find a legal way to include it in the census.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/2020-united-states-census] In response to an order from Judge Hazel, the Justice Department affirmed on July 5, 2019, that it will be seeking a route to add the citizenship question to the census, though at the time did not know which route it would take.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/2020-united-states-census] Hazel had ordered this response as, if the department was intending to add the question, he could begin determining a schedule in coordination with Judge Furman in the New York court for further proceedings and discovery in both the New York and the Maryland lawsuits.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/2020-united-states-census] Furman pointed out that the case had already run past the DOJ's own previously requested deadline of July 1 and replacing counsel would cause further delays.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/2020-united-states-census] Separate from the events in the courts, Trump has said he also considered using an executive order to place the citizenship question on the census.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/2020-united-states-census] However, on July 11 he issued Executive Order 13880 directing the Department of Commerce to obtain citizenship data from other federal agencies rather than via the census.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/2020-united-states-census] He added that "we are not backing down in our effort to determine the citizenship status of the United States population" and that data from other federal agencies would be "far more accurate" than a census question.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/2020-united-states-census] Accordingly, the department will promptly inform the courts that the government will not include a citizenship question on the 2020 decennial census." Besides federal agencies, the Department of Commerce is obtaining citizenship data from state records.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/2020-united-states-census] Joe Biden, on his first day of his presidency on January 20, 2021, issued an executive order that revoked both Trump's July 11 executive order and Trump's July 21 memo, as to have the census follow the standard practice of including the counts of undocumented immigrants within the final numbers.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/2020-united-states-census] The order did not rescind a directive for the Census Bureau to use government records to produce block-level citizenship data.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/2020-united-states-census] The state believed it would lose a congressional seat to other states that have had increased numbers of immigrants in the last decade.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/2020-united-states-census] The motion was granted by the end of 2018.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/2020-united-states-census] As the census question case continued, the Census Bureau spoke of other means to obtain immigration data, and Barr, referencing the Alabama suit, said that "for example, there is a current dispute over whether illegal aliens can be included for apportionment purposes.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/2020-united-states-census] Depending on the resolution of that dispute, this data may be relevant to those considerations.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/2020-united-states-census] We will be studying this issue." Spurred by Barr's comments that the government would not defend itself in the case, a coalition of fifteen states and other groups also moved to intervene, which was granted by September 2019.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/2020-united-states-census] On July 21, 2020, President Trump signed a memo to the Department of Commerce, "Memorandum on Excluding Illegal Aliens from the Apportionment Base Following the 2020 Census" with instructions not to include illegal immigrants in the census totals for purposes of apportionment.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/2020-united-states-census] The memo said the Constitution does not define which "persons" must be included in the apportionment base, and past censuses have excluded some legal immigrants in the country temporarily, justifying the change.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/2020-united-states-census] Law and census experts said this was an invalid interpretation as past case law has supported inclusion of "whole persons" including illegal immigrants, and the ACLU immediately said they planned to file a lawsuit against the administration over the memo.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/2020-united-states-census] Common Cause, the city of Atlanta, and other groups and individuals filed the first suit seeking an injunction to prevent the government from executing on the memo a week after it was signed in the United States District Court for the District of Columbia.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/2020-united-states-census] On September 10, 2020, a three-judge panel of the United States District Court for the Southern District of New York unanimously rejected the order, ruling that it was so obviously illegal a lawsuit challenging it was unnecessary.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/2020-united-states-census] Eight days later, the Trump administration filed notice that it would appeal the decision directly to the Supreme Court, bypassing the circuit court appeals process.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/2020-united-states-census] The Supreme Court accepted the petition on October 16, 2020, and scheduled expedited oral arguments in the case on November 30, 2020.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/2020-united-states-census] The Court ruled in a *per curiam* decision on December 18, 2020, that the case was premature due to lack of standing and ripeness but did not rule on any of the constitutional challenges at the time.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/2020-united-states-census] The decision vacated the District Court's ruling and remanded the case to the District Court to be dismissed.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/2020-united-states-census] The Trump administration sought to complete the census count earlier than originally scheduled.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/2020-united-states-census] In September 2020, federal district court judge Lucy Koh issued a preliminary injunction against the plan to end counting on September 30 rather than the scheduled October 31, saying the Commerce Department "never articulated a satisfactory explanation".
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/2020-united-states-census] She also blocked a plan to deliver the count results to the White House by December 31, rather than the original April 2021 delivery date when Trump might be out of office.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/2020-united-states-census] On the next business day, Commerce Secretary Wilbur Ross announced the count would end October 5, as the administration appealed Koh's decision to the ninth circuit.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/2020-united-states-census] Koh ordered the government to produce documents to show the Commerce Department's reasoning.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/2020-united-states-census] The appeals court upheld Koh's ruling, and the Census Bureau announced on October 2 that the count would continue until October 31.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/2020-united-states-census] Also on October 2, Koh threatened to hold Ross in contempt for repeated violations of her order.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/2020-united-states-census] The ninth circuit decision was appealed to the Supreme Court.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/2020-united-states-census] On October 13, in a 7–1 ruling, the court issued an unsigned order granting the request to end the count early.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/2020-united-states-census] As one of his first acts in office, President Joe Biden signed Executive Order 13986 on January 20, 2021, to discontinue citizenship tabulations at the city-block level using 2020 census data with administrative records.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/2020-united-states-census] He also revoked a Trump directive that would have excluded those in the country illegally from the figures used for apportioning congressional seats among the states.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/2020-united-states-census] Researchers widely criticized the Census Bureau for intentionally making block-level data inaccurate by using differential privacy.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/2020-united-states-census] In order to purportedly prevent identification of individuals' age, gender, race, household relationships, or homeownership, "disclosure avoidance noise" was added to the data, shifting individuals between blocks, towns, or other units.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/2020-united-states-census] This can result in substantial discrepancies in minority populations and the sizes of small places.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/2020-united-states-census] For example, Monowi, Nebraska, known for being the country's smallest incorporated municipality, was incorrectly reported to have two residents instead of one.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/2020-united-states-census] Redistricting data would also be corrupted, making equal-size districts and majority-minority districts more difficult.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/2020-united-states-census] On March 10, 2022, the Census Bureau released estimates of total overcount and undercount by demographic characteristic.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/2020-united-states-census] The results found that the total Hispanic population had likely been undercounted by 4.99%, the Black population by 3.3% and *Some other race* by 4.34%.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/2020-united-states-census] Asians were estimated to have been overcounted by 2.62%, Non-Hispanic Whites by 1.64%, and Pacific Islanders by 1.28%.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/2020-united-states-census] Native Americans were estimated to have been undercounted by 0.91%; however, those living on reservations were undercounted by 5.64%, while those living elsewhere were overcounted by 3.06%.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/adams-run-south-carolina] Adams Run has a post office with ZIP code 29426, which opened on August 15, 1843.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/adams-run-south-carolina] Christ Church is one of the oldest churches in Adams Run.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/adams-run-south-carolina] It is located just a few hundred yards away from the post office.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/adams-run-south-carolina] While the congregation was organized around 1835, this church was not constructed until after the Civil War.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/adams-run-south-carolina] Completed in 1887, it was built using materials from the first church, which was located at nearby Willtown Bluff, an historic settlement.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/adams-run-south-carolina] In 1962 Christ Church merged with another church, St.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/adams-run-south-carolina] The consolidated church was called ChristSt.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/adams-run-south-carolina] The congregation is now an Anglican parish and worships in a new sanctuary across from the historic St.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/adams-run-south-carolina] Paul's; the new sanctuary was completed in 2008.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/adams-run-south-carolina] Although regular Sunday services are no longer held in the Adams Run church, ChristSt.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/adams-run-south-carolina] Paul's Church often opens the historic sanctuary for special occasions.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/adams-run-south-carolina] Christ Church at Adams Run, as well as its grounds and graveyard, are maintained by Christ St.Paul's.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/adams-run-south-carolina] The Barnwell House, Grove Plantation, King Cemetery, Summit Plantation House, Wilkinson-Boineau House, and Willtown Bluff are listed on the National Register of Historic Places.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/alaska-native] The migration of Alaska Natives' ancestors into the Alaskan region occurred thousands of years ago in multiple waves.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/alaska-native] Some present-day groups descend from a later migration event whose descendants gradually settled across northern North America.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/alaska-native] The Alaska Native's ancestors are the ones who did not migrate further south or east.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/alaska-native] Genetic evidence indicates that these groups are not closely related to the Indigenous peoples of South America.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/alaska-native] Evidence from archaeology indicates that the ancestors of Alaska Natives migrated from Asia.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/alaska-native] Anthropologists have proposed that their journey to Alaska from Asia was made possible through the Bering land bridge or by traveling across the sea.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/alaska-native] Across the Arctic and the circumpolar north, the ancestors of Alaska Natives established a variety of Indigenous cultures that developed and changed over time.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/alaska-native] These cultures demonstrated considerable ingenuity in adapting to harsh climates and environments.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/alaska-native] Historically, the defining characteristic of Alaska Native groups has often been their languages, which belong to several major language families.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/alaska-native] Currently, Alaska Natives or Native Alaskans constitute more than 20% of Alaska's population.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/alaska-native] The vast majority of Alaska Natives are either Eskaleut or Na Dene.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/alaska-native] As of 2018, Alaska Natives constituted 15.4% of the overall Alaskan population.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/alaska-native] Earlier data from the Alaskan Natives Commission estimated approximately 86,000 Alaska Natives residing in Alaska in 1990, with an additional 17,000 living outside of the state.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/alaska-native] More recently, a 2013 study conducted by the Alaska Department of Labor and Workforce Development documented over 120,000 Alaska Native Individuals within Alaska.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/alaska-native] While a significant portion of the Alaska Native populations resides in smaller villages or remote regional hubs such as Nome, Dillingham, and Bethel, there has been a notable increase in the percentage living in urban areas.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/alaska-native] According to the 2010 census, 44% of Alaska Natives lived in urban areas, a rise from 38% recorded in the 2000 census.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/alaska-native] The pre-contact population of Alaska Natives, in year 1750, before first European settlement, is estimated as around 93,800 people.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/alaska-native] In 1870 the native population of Alaska was still estimated as 70,000 people.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/alaska-native] However, the census of 1880 found only 32,996 Native Alaskans.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/alaska-native] The population of Alaska Natives then further declined to 25,450 people in 1910 (of whom 25,328 lived in Alaska and 122 in the rest of the United States).
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/alaska-native] Since 1910 the population began rebounding, and it reached 168,826 people in year 2010.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/alaska-native] Of them 124,758 lived in Alaska and 44,068 in the rest of the United States.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/alaska-native] The modern history of Alaska Natives began in the eighteenth century with the initial contact between Alaskan First Nations and Russian explorers sailing from Siberia.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/alaska-native] Subsequently, in the nineteenth century, British and American traders, coming mostly from eastern settlements in North America, arrived in the region.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/alaska-native] In some areas of Alaska, the active presence of Christian missionaries did not occur until the twentieth century.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/alaska-native] Vitus Bering spotted Alaska during an expedition.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/alaska-native] Subsequently, in the 18th century, Alaska Natives encountered Russians, with the timing of this contact varying among different Native groups across Alaska.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/alaska-native] Arriving by ship from Siberia, in the mid-eighteenth century, Russians established trade with Alaska Natives, particularly in the Aleutian Islands.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/alaska-native] They founded settlements around their trading posts, which included Russian Orthodox missionaries.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/alaska-native] These missionaries were the first to translate Christian scripture into Native languages, such as Tlingit.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/alaska-native] The lasting impact of this period is evident in the 21st century with numerous Russian Orthodox Christian congregations in Alaska composed predominantly of Alaska Natives.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/alaska-native] The Sibero-Russian *promyshlenniki*, rather than engaging in hunting and harvesting marine life themselves, coerced the Aleuts into performing this labor, enserfing the Aleuts.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/alaska-native] As news for the fur trade spread, competition among Russian companies intensified.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/alaska-native] Catherine the Great, upon ascending to the throne in 1763, expressed goodwill towards the Aleuts and encouraged fair treatment.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/alaska-native] However, the increasing competition between trading companies, which eventually consolidated into larger and more powerful corporations, led to conflicts that worsened relations with the Indigenous populations.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/alaska-native] Over time, the situation became dire for the Aleuts and other Native Alaskan people affected by Russian contact.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/alaska-native] As the animal populations declined, the Aleuts, already dependent on the new barter economy driven by the fur trade with the Russians, faced increasing pressure to take greater risks in the dangerous waters of the North Pacific to hunt for more otter.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/alaska-native] The Shelikhov-Golikov Company, and later Russian-American Company developed as a monopoly, using skirmishes and systematic violence as tools for the colonial exploitation of the Indigenous peoples.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/alaska-native] When the Aleut revolted and won some victories, the Russians retaliated with deadly force, destroying their boats and hunting equipment, leaving them no means of survival.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/alaska-native] The most devastating impact on the Aleut population during the initial two generations of Russian contact (1741/1759-1781/1799 AD) was the introduction of new diseases from Eurasia.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/alaska-native] Approximately 80% of the Aleut population perished from these infectious diseases, to which they had no immunity, unlike Europeans among whom these diseases have been endemic for centuries.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/alaska-native] The Russian Tsarist government expanded into Indigenous territory in present-day Alaska for its own geopolitical reasons.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/alaska-native] It consumed natural resources of the territory during the trading years, and Russian Orthodoxy was evangelized.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/alaska-native] Their movement into these populated areas of Indigenous communities altered the demographic and natural landscape.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/alaska-native] Historians have suggested that the Russian-American Company exploited Indigenous peoples as a source of inexpensive labor.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/alaska-native] The Russian-American Company not only used Indigenous populations for labor during the fur trade, but also held some as hostages to acquire *iasak*.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/alaska-native] Iasak, a form of taxation imposed by the Russians, was a tribute in the form of otter pelts.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/alaska-native] It was a taxation method the Russians had previously found useful in their early encounter with Indigenous communities of Siberia during the Siberian fur trade.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/alaska-native] Beaver pelts were also customary to be given to fur traders upon first contact with various communities.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/alaska-native] The Russian-American Company used military force on Indigenous families, taking them hostage until male community members produced furs for them.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/alaska-native] Otter furs on Kodiak Island and Aleutian Islands enticed the Russians to start these taxations.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/alaska-native] Robbery and maltreatment in the form of corporal punishment and the withholding of food was also present upon the arrival of fur traders.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/alaska-native] Catherine the Great dissolved the giving of tribute in 1799, but her government initiated mandatory conscription of Indigenous men between the ages of 18 and 50 to become seal hunters strictly for the Russian American Company.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/alaska-native] This mandatory labor gave the Russian American Company an edge in competition with American and British fur traders.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/alaska-native] But the conscription separated men from their families and villages, thus altering and breaking down communities.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/alaska-native] With able-bodied men away on the hunt, villages were left with little protection as only women, children, and the elderly remained behind.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/alaska-native] In addition to changes that came with conscription, the spread of disease also altered the populations of Indigenous communities.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/alaska-native] Although records kept in the period were scarce, it has been said that 80% of the pre-contact population of the Aleut people were gone by 1800.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/alaska-native] The Alaska Native population was first recorded in the 1880 United States census, and it was estimated that the population had declined from 80,000 in 1741 to 33,000 due to disease.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/alaska-native] The population continued to decline until 1910 and it was not until 1947 that this number surpassed the 1880 figure.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/alaska-native] Relationships between Indigenous women and fur traders increased as Indigenous men were away from villages.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/alaska-native] This resulted in marriages and children that would come to be known as Creole peoples, children who were Indigenous and Russian.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/alaska-native] To reduce hostilities with Aleutian communities, it became policy for fur traders to enter into marriage with Indigenous women.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/alaska-native] The Creole population increased in the territory controlled by the Russian American Company.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/alaska-native] The growth of the Russian Orthodox Church was another important tactic in the colonization and conversion of Indigenous populations.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/alaska-native] Ioann Veniaminov, who later became Saint Innocent of Alaska, was an important missionary who carried out the Orthodox Church's agenda to Christianize Indigenous populations.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/alaska-native] The church encouraged Creole children to follow Russian Orthodox Christianity, while the Russian American Company provided them with an education.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/alaska-native] Many Orthodox missionaries, like Herman of Alaska, defended Natives from exploitation.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/alaska-native] Creole people were believed to have high levels of loyalty toward the Russian crown and Russian American Company.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/alaska-native] After completing their education, children were often sent to Russia, where they would study skills such as mapmaking, theology, and military intelligence.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/alaska-native] In the 1850s Russia lost much of its interest in Alaska.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/alaska-native] Alaska's abundance of natural resources, particularly gold, drew the interest of the United States.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/alaska-native] In 1867, the United States bought Alaska from Russia.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/alaska-native] This purchase happened without considering the opinions of the Native Alaskans, who were not regarded as citizens at the time.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/alaska-native] The land traditionally belonging to Alaska Natives was treated as "open land," allowing white settlers to claim it without providing any compensation or recognition to the Native people living there.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/alaska-native] The only educational opportunities available for Alaska Natives were in schools established by religious missionaries.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/alaska-native] Many white settlers failed to appreciate the complex and well-developed cultures that Alaska Natives had created to thrive in their challenging environment.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/alaska-native] Instead, they viewed them as inferior to European Americans, which aligned with white supremacist ideologies.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/alaska-native] The Klondike Gold Rush of 1896–1898 led to increased white settlement in Alaska and brought discriminatory practices against Indigenous peoples.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/alaska-native] American settlers imposed racial segregation and discriminatory laws similar to Jim Crow laws, which severely limited Alaska Natives' opportunities and cultural practices, effectively treating them as second-class citizens.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/alaska-native] This segregation manifested in various ways, including "whites only" signs that prevented natives from entering certain buildings.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/alaska-native] Educational discrimination was also prevalent.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/alaska-native] In an 1880 court case, a child was barred from attending school with Americans because his stepfather was native.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/alaska-native] Children of mixed heritage could only attend American schools if their families abandoned their native culture.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/alaska-native] Simultaneously, the U.S. government implemented policies to disrupt Alaska Native family structures.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/alaska-native] Federal records show that disrupting native family units was a deliberate part of Federal Indian policy aimed at assimilating Indigenous children.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/alaska-native] The Federal Indian Boarding School Initiative played a major role in creating intergenerational trauma by removing children from their native villages and placing them in off-reservation boarding schools alongside children from other tribes.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/alaska-native] This system created artificial communities of Indigenous children throughout the boarding school network, resulting in new Indigenous family structures depending on whether children returned to their native villages or settled elsewhere after completing their education.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/alaska-native] These policies prohibited Alaska Native children from speaking their native languages, wearing traditional clothing, associating with other natives, consuming traditional foods, or practicing their religions.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/alaska-native] The resulting family separation and cultural eradication caused significant intergenerational trauma.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/alaska-native] In 1912, the Alaska Native Brotherhood (ANB) was formed to help fight for citizenship rights.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/alaska-native] The Alaska Native Sisterhood (ANS) was created in 1915.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/alaska-native] Also in 1915, the Alaska Territorial legislature passed a law allowing Alaskan Natives the right to vote – but on the condition that they give up their cultural customs and traditions.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/alaska-native] The Indian Citizenship Act, passed in 1924, gave all Native Americans United States citizenship.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/alaska-native] ANB began to hold a great deal of political power in the 1920s.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/alaska-native] They protested the segregation of Alaska Natives in public areas and institutions, and also staged boycotts.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/alaska-native] Alberta Schenck (Inupiaq) staged a well-publicized protest against segregation in a movie theater in 1944.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/alaska-native] With the help of Elizabeth Peratrovich (Tlingit), the Alaska Equal Rights Act of 1945 was passed, ending segregation in Alaska.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/alaska-native] In 1942, during World War II, the United States forced evacuation of around nine hundred Aleuts from the Aleutian Islands.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/alaska-native] The idea was to remove the Aleuts from a potential combat zone during World War II for their own protection, but European Americans living in the same area were not forced to leave.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/alaska-native] The removal was handled so poorly that many Aleuts died after they were evacuated; the elderly and children had the highest mortality rates.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/alaska-native] Survivors returned to the islands to find their homes and possessions destroyed or looted.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/alaska-native] Civil rights activists such as Alberta Schenck Adams and Elizabeth Peratrovich protested discriminatory laws against Native Alaskans with what were effectively sit-ins and lobbying.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/alaska-native] The Alaska Equal Rights Act of 1945, the first anti-discrimination state law in the U.S., occurred as a result of these protests.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/alaska-native] It entitled all Alaskans to "full and equal enjoyment" of public areas and businesses, a ban on segregating signs, with discriminatory actions punishable by a $250 fine and up to 30 days in jail.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/alaska-native] Alaska became part of the United States in 1959 upon President Dwight D.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/alaska-native] Eisenhower recognizing Alaska as the 49th state.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/alaska-native] In 1971, with the support of Alaska Native leaders such as Emil Notti, Willie Hensley, and Byron Mallott, the U.S.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/alaska-native] Congress passed the Alaska Native Claims Settlement Act (ANCSA), which settled land and financial claims for lands and resources which the Alaska Natives had lost to European-Americans.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/alaska-native] It provided for the establishment of thirteen Alaska Native Regional Corporations to administer those claims.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/alaska-native] Similar to the separately defined status of the Canadian Inuit and First Nations in Canada, which are recognized as distinct peoples, in the United States, Alaska Natives or Native Alaskans are in some respects treated separately by the government from other Native Americans in the United States.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/alaska-native] This is in part related to their interactions with the U.S. government which occurred in a different historical period than its interactions during the period of westward expansion during the 19th century.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/alaska-native] Europeans and Americans did not have sustained encounters with the Alaska Natives until the late 19th and early 20th centuries when many were attracted to the region in gold rushes.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/alaska-native] The Alaska Natives were not allotted individual title in severalty to land under the Dawes Act of 1887 but were instead treated under the Alaska Native Allotment Act of 1906.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/alaska-native] The Allotment Act was repealed in 1971, following ANSCA, at which time reservations were ended.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/alaska-native] Another characteristic difference is that Alaska Native tribal governments do not have the power to collect taxes for business transacted on tribal land, per the United States Supreme Court decision in *Alaska v.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/alaska-native] Native Village of Venetie Tribal Government* (1998).
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/alaska-native] Except for the Tsimshian, Alaska Natives no longer hold reservations but do control some lands.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/alaska-native] Under the Marine Mammal Protection Act of 1972, Alaska Natives reserve the right to harvest whales and other marine mammals.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/alaska-native] Four Indigenous tribes in Alaska, the Shishmaref, Kivalina, Shaktoolik, and Newtok tribes, are among America's first climate refugees due to the impacts of sea ice melting and increased wildfires in their regions.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/alaska-native] Climate change has created extensive challenges for Alaska's native peoples, including increased vulnerability to disease, mental health issues, physical injuries, and food and water insecurity.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/alaska-native] According to the Environmental Protection Agency (EPA), coastal erosion from sea ice loss is displacing native communities.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/alaska-native] This melting also disrupts the migration patterns of animals that tribes depend on for sustenance, while eliminating traditional places to store harvested food.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/alaska-native] As permafrost thaws, existing infrastructure becomes unstable, leading to the collapse of Native villages.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/alaska-native] The Shishmaref, Kivalina, Shaktoolik, and Newtok tribes are situated on Alaska's west coast, where rising sea levels have intensified storm surges that erode their coastlines.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/alaska-native] These communities face forced migration because there is no suitable nearby land to relocate to, requiring them to abandon their traditional ways of life.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/alaska-native] Predictions indicate that a significant climate event could completely submerge these tribal lands in fewer than fifteen years.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/alaska-native] The changing climate has heightened safety risks for Alaska Natives.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/alaska-native] While thick ice layers were historically present year-round, warming temperatures have thinned the ice, increasing incidents of people falling through—a dangerous situation that leads to additional health concerns even for survivors.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/alaska-native] Water insecurity and deteriorating infrastructure have created sanitation problems, contributing to an increase in respiratory illnesses across Alaska.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/alaska-native] In 2005, pneumonia became the leading cause of hospitalizations in these regions.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/alaska-native] Many affected communities experience significant psychological stress due to both the immediate impacts of climate change and the complex challenges of relocation without established policies or pathways.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/alaska-native] Additional stress comes from infrastructure damage caused by thawing permafrost, with minimal regulatory guidance beyond the Alaskan government's recommendations to avoid building on permafrost or to use extra insulation on foundation walls.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/alaska-native] Food security has also deteriorated as animals relocate to more suitable habitats.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/alaska-native] Traditional underground ice cellars, once frozen year-round, now thaw during summer months, rendering food supplies inedible.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/alaska-native] Gathering of subsistence food continues to be an important economic and cultural activity for many Alaska Natives.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/alaska-native] In Utqiaġvik, Alaska, in 2005, more than 91 percent of the Iñupiat households which were interviewed still participated in the local subsistence economy, compared with the approximately 33 percent of non-Iñupiat households who used wild resources obtained from hunting, fishing, or gathering.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/alaska-native] But, unlike many tribes in the contiguous United States, Alaska Natives do not have treaties with the United States that protect their subsistence rights, except for the right to harvest whales and other marine mammals.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/alaska-native] The Alaska Native Claims Settlement Act explicitly extinguished aboriginal hunting and fishing rights in the state of Alaska.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p01] The **American Civil War** (April 12, 1861 – May 26, 1865; also known by other names) was a civil war in the United States between the Union ("the North") and the Confederacy ("the South"), which was formed in 1861 by states that had seceded from the Union to preserve slavery in the United States.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p01] The South saw slavery as threatened because of the election of Abraham Lincoln and the growing abolitionist movement in the North.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p01] The war ended with Union victory, the dissolution of the Confederacy and the abolition of slavery, freeing four million African Americans.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p01] Decades of controversy over slavery came to a head when Abraham Lincoln, a Republican who opposed slavery's expansion, won the 1860 presidential election.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p01] Seven slave states in the South responded to Lincoln's victory by seceding from the United States and forming the Confederate States of America.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p01] The Confederacy seized US forts and other federal assets in the South.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p01] The war began on April 12, 1861, when the Confederacy bombarded Fort Sumter in South Carolina.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p01] A wave of enthusiasm for war swept over the North and South, as military recruitment soared.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p01] Four more Southern states seceded after the war began and, led by its president, Jefferson Davis, the Confederacy comprised eleven states, containing a third of the US population.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p01] Four years of intense combat, mostly in the South, ensued.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p01] During 1861–1862 in the western theater, the Union made permanent gains, though in the eastern theater the conflict was inconclusive.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p01] The abolition of slavery became a Union war goal on January 1, 1863, when Lincoln issued the Emancipation Proclamation, which declared all slaves in rebel states to be free, applying to more than 3.5 million of the 4 million enslaved people in the country.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p01] To the west, the Union first destroyed the Confederacy's river navy by the summer of 1862, then much of its western armies, and seized New Orleans.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p01] The successful 1863 Union siege of Vicksburg split the Confederacy in two at the Mississippi River, while Confederate general Robert E.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p01] Lee's incursion north failed at the Battle of Gettysburg.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p01] Grant's western successes led Lincoln to promote him to command of all Union armies in 1864.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p01] Inflicting an ever-tightening naval blockade of Confederate ports, the Union marshaled resources and manpower to attack the Confederacy from all directions.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p01] This led to the fall of Atlanta in 1864 to Union general William Tecumseh Sherman, followed by his March to the Sea, which culminated in his taking Savannah.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p01] The last significant battles raged around the ten-month Siege of Petersburg, gateway to the Confederate capital of Richmond.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p01] The Confederates abandoned Richmond, and on April 9, 1865, Lee surrendered to Grant following the Battle of Appomattox Court House, setting in motion the end of the war.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p01] Lincoln lived to see this victory but was shot by an assassin on April 14, dying the next day.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p01] By the end of the war, much of the South's infrastructure had been destroyed.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p01] The Confederacy collapsed, the Thirteenth Amendment abolished slavery, and four million enslaved black people were freed.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p01] The war-torn nation then entered the Reconstruction era in an attempt to rebuild the country, bring the former Confederate states back into the United States, and grant civil rights to freed slaves.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p01] The war is one of the most extensively studied and written about episodes in the history of the United States.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p01] It remains the subject of cultural and historiographical debate.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p01] Of continuing interest is the myth of the Lost Cause of the Confederacy.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p01] The war was among the first to use industrial warfare.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p01] Railroads, the electrical telegraph, steamships, the ironclad warship, and mass-produced weapons were widely used.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p01] The war left an estimated 700,000 soldiers dead, along with an undetermined number of civilian deaths, making it the deadliest in American history.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p01] The technology and brutality of the Civil War foreshadowed the coming world wars.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p01] The origins of the war were rooted in the desire of the Southern states to preserve the institution of slavery.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p01] Historians in the 21st century overwhelmingly agree on the centrality of slavery in the conflict—at least for the Southern states.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p01] They disagree on the North's reasons for refusing to allow the Southern states to secede.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p01] The pseudo-historical Lost Cause ideology denies that slavery was the principal cause of the secession, a view disproven by historical evidence, including the seceding states' own secession documents.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p01] The principal political battle leading to Southern secession was over whether slavery would expand into the Western territories destined to become states.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p01] Initially Congress had admitted new states into the Union in pairs, one slave and one free.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p01] This had kept a sectional balance in the Senate but not in the House of Representatives, as free states outstripped slave states in numbers of eligible voters.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p01] Thus, at mid-19th century, the free-versus-slave status of the new territories was a critical issue, both for the North, where anti-slavery sentiment had grown, and for the South, where the fear of slavery's abolition had grown.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p01] Another factor leading to secession and the formation of the Confederacy was the development of white Southern nationalism in the preceding decades.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p01] The primary reason for the North to reject secession was to preserve the Union, a cause based on American nationalism.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p01] Background factors in the run up to the Civil War were partisan politics, abolitionism, nullification versus secession, Southern and Northern nationalism, expansionism, economics, and modernization in the antebellum period.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p01] Abraham Lincoln won the 1860 presidential election.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p01] Southern leaders feared Lincoln would stop slavery's expansion and put it on a course toward extinction.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p01] His victory triggered declarations of secession by seven slave states of the Deep South, all of whose riverfront or coastal economies were based on cotton that was cultivated by slave labor.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p01] Lincoln was not inaugurated until March 4, 1861, four months after his 1860 election, which afforded the South time to prepare for war.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p01] Nationalists in the North and "Unionists" in the South refused to accept the declarations of secession, and no foreign government ever recognized the Confederacy.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p01] The US government, under President James Buchanan, refused to relinquish the nation's forts, which the Confederacy claimed were located in their territory.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p01] According to Lincoln, the American people had demonstrated, beginning with their victory in the American Revolution and Revolutionary War and subsequent establishment of a sovereign nation, that they could successfully establish and administer a republic.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p01] Yet, Lincoln believed, a question remained unanswered: Could the nation be maintained as a republic, with its government selected by vote of the people, in the face of internal attempts to destroy it or separate from it?
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p01] Lincoln's election provoked South Carolina's legislature to call a state convention to consider secession.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p01] South Carolina had done more than any other state to advance the notion that a state had the right to nullify federal laws and even secede.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p01] On December 20, 1860, the convention unanimously voted to secede and adopted a secession declaration.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p01] It argued for states' rights for slave owners but complained about states' rights in the North in the form of resistance to the federal Fugitive Slave Act, claiming that Northern states were not fulfilling their obligations to assist in the return of fugitive slaves.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p01] The "cotton states" of Mississippi, Florida, Alabama, Georgia, Louisiana, and Texas followed suit, seceding in January and February 1861.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p01] Among the ordinances of secession, those of Texas, Alabama, and Virginia mentioned the plight of the "slaveholding states" at the hands of Northern abolitionists.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p01] The rest made no mention of slavery but were brief announcements by the legislatures of the dissolution of ties to the Union.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p01] However, at least four—South Carolina, Mississippi, Georgia, and Texas—provided detailed reasons for their secession, all blaming the movement to abolish slavery and its influence over the North.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p01] Southern states believed that the Fugitive Slave Clause made slaveholding a constitutional right.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p01] These states agreed to form a new federal government, the Confederate States of America, on February 4, 1861.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p01] They took control of federal forts and other properties within their boundaries, with little resistance from outgoing president James Buchanan, whose term ended on March 4.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p01] Buchanan said the Dred Scott decision was proof the Southern states had no reason to secede and that the Union "was intended to be perpetual".
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p01] He added, however, that "The power by force of arms to compel a State to remain in the Union" was not among the "enumerated powers granted to Congress".
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p01] A quarter of the US army—the Texas garrison—was surrendered in February to state forces by its general, David E.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p01] West Virginia left the rest of Virginia and joined the Union as West Virginia because of the slavery issue.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p01] As Southerners resigned their Senate and House seats, Republicans could pass projects that had been blocked.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p01] These included the Morrill Tariff, land grant colleges, a Homestead Act, a transcontinental railroad, the National Bank Act, authorization of United States Notes by the Legal Tender Act of 1862, the end of slavery in the District of Columbia, and a ban on slavery in the territories.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p01] The Revenue Act of 1861 introduced an income tax to help finance the war.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p01] In December 1860, the Crittenden Compromise was proposed to re-establish the Missouri Compromise line, by constitutionally banning slavery in territories to the north of it, while permitting it to the south.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p01] The Compromise would likely have prevented secession, but Lincoln and the Republicans rejected it.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p01] Lincoln stated that any compromise that would extend slavery would bring down the Union.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p01] A February peace conference met in Washington, proposing a solution similar to the Compromise; it was rejected by Congress.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p01] The Republicans proposed the Corwin Amendment, an alternative, not to interfere with slavery where it existed, but the South regarded it as insufficient.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p01] The remaining eight slave states rejected pleas to join the Confederacy, following a no-vote in Virginia's First Secessionist Convention on April 4.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p01] On March 4, Lincoln was sworn in as president.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p01] In his first inaugural address, he argued that the Constitution was a *more perfect union* than the earlier Articles of Confederation and Perpetual Union, was a binding contract, and that secession was "legally void".
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p01] He did not intend to invade Southern states, nor to end slavery where it existed, but he said he would use force to maintain possession of federal property, including forts, arsenals, mints, and customhouses that had been seized.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p01] "The mails, unless repelled, will continue to be furnished in all parts of the Union." Where conditions did not allow peaceful enforcement of federal law, US marshals and judges would be withdrawn.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p01] No mention was made of bullion lost from mints.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p01] He stated that it would be US policy "to collect the duties and imposts"; "there will be no invasion, no using of force against or among the people anywhere" that would justify an armed revolution.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p01] His speech closed with a plea for restoration of the bonds of union, famously calling on "the mystic chords of memory" binding the two regions.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p01] The Confederacy sent delegates to Washington to negotiate a peace treaty.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p01] Lincoln rejected negotiations, because he claimed that the Confederacy was not a legitimate government and to make a treaty with it would recognize it as such.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p01] Lincoln instead attempted to negotiate directly with the governors of seceded states, whose administrations he continued to recognize.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p01] Complicating Lincoln's attempts to defuse the crisis was Secretary of State William H.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p01] Seward, who had been Lincoln's rival for the Republican nomination.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p01] Embittered by his defeat, Seward agreed to support Lincoln's candidacy only after he was guaranteed the executive office then considered the second most powerful.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p01] In the early stages of Lincoln's presidency Seward held little regard for him, due to his perceived inexperience.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p01] Seward viewed himself as the de facto head of government, the "prime minister" behind the throne.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p01] Seward attempted to engage in unauthorized and indirect negotiations that failed.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p01] Lincoln was determined to hold all remaining Union-occupied forts in the seceded states: Fort Pickens, Fort Jefferson, and Fort Taylor in Florida, and Fort Sumter in South Carolina.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p01] The American Civil War began on April 12, 1861, when Confederate forces opened fire on the Union-held Fort Sumter.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p01] Fort Sumter is located in the harbor of Charleston, South Carolina.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p01] Its status had been contentious for months.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p01] Outgoing president Buchanan had dithered in reinforcing its garrison, commanded by Major Robert Anderson.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p01] Anderson took matters into his own hands and on December 26, 1860, under the cover of darkness, sailed the garrison from the poorly placed Fort Moultrie to the stalwart island Fort Sumter.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p01] Anderson's actions catapulted him to hero status in the North.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p01] An attempt to resupply the fort on January 9, 1861, failed and nearly started the war then, but an informal truce held.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p01] On March 5, Lincoln was informed the fort was low on supplies.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p01] Fort Sumter proved a key challenge to Lincoln's administration.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p01] Back-channel dealing by Seward with the Confederates undermined Lincoln's decision-making; Seward wanted to pull out.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p01] But a firm hand by Lincoln tamed Seward, who was a staunch Lincoln ally thereafter.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p01] Lincoln decided holding the fort, which would require reinforcing it, was the only workable option.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p01] On April 6, Lincoln informed the Governor of South Carolina that a ship with food but no ammunition would attempt to supply the fort.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p01] James McPherson describes this win-win approach as "the first sign of the mastery that would mark Lincoln's presidency"; the Union would win if it could resupply and hold the fort, and the South would be the aggressor if it opened fire on an unarmed ship supplying starving men.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p01] An April 9 Confederate cabinet meeting resulted in Davis ordering General P.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p01] Beauregard to take the fort before supplies reached it.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p01] At 4:30 a.m. on April 12, Confederate forces fired the first of 4,000 shells at the fort; it fell the next day.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p01] The loss of Fort Sumter lit a patriotic fire under the North.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p01] On April 15, Lincoln called on the states to field 75,000 militiamen for 90 days; impassioned Union states met the quotas quickly.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p01] On May 3, 1861, Lincoln called for an additional 42,000 volunteers for three years.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p01] Shortly after this, Virginia, Tennessee, Arkansas, and North Carolina seceded and joined the Confederacy.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p01] To reward Virginia, the Confederate capital was moved to Richmond.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p01] Maryland, Delaware, Missouri, and Kentucky, known as the border states, were slave states that had not seceded and whose people had divided loyalties to the North and South, with some men enlisting in the Union Army and others in the Confederate Army.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p01] West Virginia may be compared to the border states because it had slavery after it separated from Virginia and was admitted to the Union on June 20, 1863, but it was admitted under a plan of gradual emancipation known as the Willey Amendment.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p01] Maryland's territory surrounded Washington, D.C., and could cut it off from the North.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p01] It had anti-Lincoln officials who tolerated anti-army rioting in Baltimore and the burning of bridges, both aimed at hindering the passage of troops to Washington, D.C., and the South.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p01] Maryland's legislature voted overwhelmingly to stay in the Union, but rejected hostilities with its southern neighbors, voting to close Maryland's rail lines to prevent their use for war.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p01] Lincoln responded by establishing martial law and suspending habeas corpus in Maryland, along with sending in militia units.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p01] In *Ex parte Merryman*, Chief Justice Roger Taney found that only Congress could suspend habeas corpus, but Lincoln ignored his ruling.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p01] Lincoln took control of Maryland and the District of Columbia by seizing prominent figures, including arresting one-third of the members of the Maryland General Assembly, who were pro-Confederate, on September 17, 1861, the day it intended to reconvene.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p01] All were held without trial at Fort McHenry in Baltimore.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p01] In September 1861, federal troops imprisoned a Baltimore newspaper editor, Frank Key Howard, after he criticized Lincoln in an editorial for ignoring Chief Justice Taney's ruling in *Ex parte Merryman*.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p01] Howard wrote a book about his prison experiences, which was published early in 1863.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p01] It "stressed the crowded conditions and spartan hardships of prison life ... [and] likened the conditions in Fort Lafayette to those on 'a slave-ship, on the middle passage'".
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p01] In Missouri, an elected convention on secession voted to remain in the Union.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p01] When pro-Confederate Governor Claiborne Fox Jackson called out the state militia, it was attacked by federal forces under General Nathaniel Lyon, who chased the governor and rest of the State Guard to the southwestern corner of Missouri (see Missouri secession).
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p01] Early in the war the Confederacy controlled southern Missouri through the Confederate government of Missouri but was driven out after 1862.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p01] In the resulting vacuum, the convention on secession reconvened and took power as the Unionist provisional government of Missouri.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p01] Kentucky did not secede but declared itself neutral.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p01] When Confederate forces entered in September 1861, its neutrality ended and the state reaffirmed its Union status while maintaining slavery.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p01] Its jurisdiction extended only as far as Confederate battle lines in the Commonwealth, which at its greatest extent was over half the state, and it went into exile after October 1862.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p01] After Virginia's secession, a Unionist government in Wheeling asked 48 counties to vote on an ordinance to create a new state in October 1861.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p01] A voter turnout of 34 percent approved the statehood bill (96 percent approving).
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p01] Twenty-four secessionist counties were included in the new state, and the ensuing guerrilla war engaged about 40,000 federal troops for much of the war.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p01] Congress admitted West Virginia to the Union on June 20, 1863.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p01] West Virginians provided about 20,000 soldiers to each side in the war.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p01] A Unionist secession attempt occurred in East Tennessee but was suppressed by the Confederacy, which arrested over 3,000 men suspected of loyalty to the Union; they were held without trial.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p01] The Civil War was marked by intense and frequent battles.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p01] Over four years, 237 named battles were fought, along with many smaller actions, often characterized by their bitter intensity and high casualties.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p01] Historian John Keegan described it as "one of the most ferocious wars ever fought", where in many cases the only target was the enemy's soldiers.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p01] As the Confederate states organized, the US Army numbered 16,000, while Northern governors began mobilizing their militias.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p01] The Confederate Congress authorized up to 100,000 troops in February.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p01] By May, Jefferson Davis was pushing for another 100,000 soldiers for one year or the duration, and the US Congress responded in kind.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p01] In the first year of the war, both sides had more volunteers than they could effectively train and equip.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p01] After the initial enthusiasm faded, relying on young men who came of age each year was not enough.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p01] Both sides enacted draft laws (conscription) to encourage or force volunteering, though relatively few were drafted.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p01] The Confederacy passed a draft law in April 1862 for men aged 18 to 35, with exemptions for overseers, government officials, and clergymen.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p01] The US Congress followed in July, authorizing a militia draft within states that could not meet their quota with volunteers.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p01] European immigrants joined the Union Army in large numbers, including 177,000 born in Germany and 144,000 in Ireland.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p01] About 50,000 Canadians served, around 2,500 of whom were black.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p01] When the Emancipation Proclamation went into effect in January 1863, ex-slaves were energetically recruited to meet state quotas.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p01] States and local communities offered higher cash bonuses for white volunteers.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p01] Congress tightened the draft law in March 1863.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p01] Men selected in the draft could provide substitutes or, until mid-1864, pay commutation money.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p01] Many eligibles pooled their money to cover the cost of anyone drafted.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p01] Families used the substitute provision to select which man should go into the army and which should stay home.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p01] There was much evasion and resistance to the draft, especially in Catholic areas.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p01] The New York City draft riots in July 1863 involved Irish immigrants who had been signed up as citizens to swell the vote of the city's Democratic political machine, not realizing it made them liable for the draft.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p01] Of the 168,649 men procured for the Union through the draft, 117,986 were substitutes, leaving only 50,663 who were conscripted.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p01] In the North and South, draft laws were highly unpopular.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p01] In the North, some 120,000 men evaded conscription, many fleeing to Canada, and another 280,000 soldiers deserted during the war.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p01] At least 100,000 Southerners deserted, about 10 percent of the total.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p01] Southern desertion was high because many soldiers were more concerned about the fate of their local area than the Southern cause.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p01] In the North, "bounty jumpers" enlisted to collect the generous bonus, deserted, then re-enlisted under a different name for a second bonus; 141 were caught and executed.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p01] From a tiny frontier force in 1860, the Union and Confederate armies grew into the "largest and most efficient armies in the world" within a few years.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p01] Some European observers at the time dismissed them as amateur and unprofessional, but historian John Keegan concluded that each outmatched the French, Prussian, and Russian armies, and without the Atlantic, could have threatened any of them with defeat.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p01] Unionism was strong in certain areas within the Confederacy.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p01] As many as 100,000 men living in states under Confederate control served in the Union Army or pro-Union guerrilla groups.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p01] Although they came from all classes, most Southern Unionists differed socially, culturally, and economically from their region's dominant prewar, slave-owning planter class.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p01] At the beginning of the Civil War, a parole system operated, under which captives agreed not to fight until exchanged.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p01] They were held in camps run by their army, paid, but not allowed to perform any military duties.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p01] The system of exchanges collapsed in 1863 when the Confederacy refused to exchange black prisoners.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p01] After that, approximately 56,000 of the 409,000 POWs died in prisons, accounting for 10 percent of the conflict's fatalities.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p01] Leonard writes that between 500 and 1,000 women enlisted as soldiers on both sides, disguised as men.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p01] Women also served as spies, resistance activists, nurses, and hospital personnel.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p01] Women served on the Union hospital ship *Red Rover* and nursed Union and Confederate troops at field hospitals.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p01] Mary Edwards Walker, the only woman ever to receive the Medal of Honor, served in the Union Army and was given the medal for treating the wounded during the war.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p01] One woman, Jennie Hodgers, fought for the Union under the name Albert D.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p01] After she returned to civilian life, she continued to live as a man until she died in 1915 at the age of 71.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p01] During the war, women in the North advocated for social reforms and created ladies' aid societies, also called soldiers' aid societies, which provided supplies to soldiers on the battlefield and cared for sick and wounded soldiers.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p01] Women in the North also held military rallies, village parades, and charity bazaars.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p01] Anthony saw that supporting the war effort was a way to pave the future for women's suffrage movements.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p01] In her appeal to Northern women's loyalty, Anthony challenged the inconsistencies of the nation's founding ideal and its actual practices concerning equality among women.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p01] Northern women during the Civil War also made great strides in the workforce, as they helped contribute to the war effort by stepping into roles that were traditionally held by men.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p01] While women rarely worked in factories before the war, many filled men's places as they felt they could erase some of the boundaries that separated them from male preserves of power.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p01] Women were important in the workforce as they prepared and packed provisions, sewed uniforms and havelocks, and knitted socks and mittens.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p01] By entering these new environments, women made significant progress in the fight for women's equality in the workforce.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p01] Northern women were also essential in the wartime support, as they were active participants in the war narrative.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p01] While women were not allowed to fight on the battlefield in the Civil War, they exhibited a patriotism that gave them the strength to maintain courage for themselves as well as their households.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p01] While their men were off at war, Northern women created a landscape that emphasized love, sacrifice, and the nurturing of men's courage.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p01] This is demonstrated in feminized war literature that encouraged, expressed, and valorized men's patriotism.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p01] Women's unwavering encouragement and affection towards fighting men became a cornerstone of the war effort as it helped sustain the spirits of the men on the frontlines.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p01] Confederate women during the Civil War focused on preserving the central economic institution of the Old South: the plantation.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p01] With so many men away at war, women were left with the land and the slaves.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p01] While some women hired male overseers to assist them in directing and maintaining newly female-headed plantations, other women decided to stay at the plantations and run the plantations themselves.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p01] Southern women became focused on keeping the economic structure of the South as they dealt with increasingly rebellious slaves.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p01] The South relied on enslaved labor because it was an agrarian economy.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p01] A good number of enslaved men labored for the Confederate army during the war, which meant that enslaved women and children were increasingly at the center of the work force on the plantations.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p01] White Southern women struggled to maintain morale on the home front as they dealt with problems without men.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p01] Although Southern women were devoted to the Confederacy, many requested that their sons and husbands be discharged from the military to help them at home.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p01] Eliza Adams wrote to the Confederate government to appeal for exemptions for her sons' military service, as she had sent five sons and also sons-in-laws to fight for the Confederacy.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p01] Southern women were torn between their patriotic ideals and their daily realities of life on the home front.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p01] The Union Navy in 1861 was relatively small but, by 1865, expanded rapidly to 6,000 officers, 45,000 sailors, and 671 vessels totaling 510,396 tons.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p01] Its mission was to blockade Confederate ports, control the river system, defend against Confederate raiders on the high seas, and be ready for a possible war with the British Royal Navy.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p01] The main riverine war was fought in the West, where major rivers gave access to the Confederate heartland.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p01] The US Navy eventually controlled the Red, Tennessee, Cumberland, Mississippi, and Ohio rivers.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p01] In the East, the Navy shelled Confederate forts and supported coastal army operations.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p01] The Civil War occurred during the early stages of the industrial revolution, leading to naval innovations, including the ironclad warship.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p01] The Confederacy, recognizing the need to counter the Union's naval superiority, built or converted over 130 vessels, including 26 ironclads.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p01] Despite these efforts, Confederate ships were largely unsuccessful against Union ironclads.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p01] The Union Navy used timberclads, tinclads, and armored gunboats.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p01] The Confederacy experimented with the submarine CSS *Hunley*, which proved unsuccessful, and with the ironclad CSS *Virginia*, rebuilt from the sunken Union ship *Merrimack*.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p01] On March 8, 1862, *Virginia* inflicted significant damage on the Union's wooden fleet, but the next day, the first Union ironclad, USS *Monitor*, arrived to challenge it in the Chesapeake Bay.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p01] The resulting three-hour Battle of Hampton Roads was a draw, proving ironclads were effective warships.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p01] The Confederacy scuttled the *Virginia* to prevent its capture, while the Union built many copies of the *Monitor*.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p01] The Confederacy's efforts to obtain warships from Great Britain failed, as Britain had no interest in selling warships to a nation at war with a stronger enemy and feared souring relations with the US.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p01] By early 1861, General Winfield Scott had devised the Anaconda Plan to win the war with minimal bloodshed, calling for a blockade of the Confederacy to suffocate the South into surrender.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p01] Lincoln adopted parts of the plan but opted for a more active war strategy.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p01] In April 1861, Lincoln announced a blockade of all Southern ports; commercial ships could not get insurance, ending regular traffic.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p01] The South blundered by embargoing cotton exports before the blockade was fully effective; by the time they reversed this decision, it was too late.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p01] "King Cotton" was dead, as the South could export less than 10% of its cotton.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p01] The blockade shut down the ten Confederate seaports with railheads that moved almost all the cotton.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p01] By June 1861, warships were stationed off the principal Southern ports, and a year later nearly 300 ships were in service.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p01] The Confederates began the war short on military supplies, which the agrarian South could not produce in adequate numbers.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p01] Northern arms manufacturers were restricted by an embargo, ending existing and future contracts with the South.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p01] The Confederacy turned to foreign sources, connecting with financiers and companies like S.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p01] Isaac, Campbell & Company and the London Armoury Company in Britain, becoming the Confederacy's main source of arms.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p01] To transport arms safely to the Confederacy, British investors built small, fast, steam-driven blockade runners that traded arms and supplies from Britain, through Bermuda, Cuba, and the Bahamas in exchange for high-priced cotton.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p01] Many were lightweight and designed for speed, only carrying small amounts of cotton back to England.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p01] When the Union Navy seized a blockade runner, the ship and cargo were condemned as a prize of war and sold, with proceeds given to the Navy sailors; the captured crewmen, mostly British, were released.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p01] The Southern economy nearly collapsed during the war due to multiple factors, the most notable being severe food shortages, failing railroads, loss of control over key rivers, foraging by Northern armies, and the seizure of animals and crops by Confederate forces.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p01] Historians agree the blockade was a major factor in ruining the Confederate economy; however, Wise argues blockade runners provided enough of a lifeline to allow Robert E.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p01] Lee, a Confederate general, to continue fighting for additional months, as a result of supplies that included 400,000 rifles, lead, blankets, and boots that the Confederate economy could no longer supply.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p01] The Confederate cotton crop became nearly useless, which cut off the Confederacy's primary income source.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p01] Critical imports were scarce, and coastal trade also largely ended.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p01] The blockade's success was not measured by the few ships, which slipped through, but by the thousands that never tried.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p01] European merchant ships could not obtain insurance for their ships and transport, and were too slow to evade the blockade, leading them to cease docking in Confederate ports.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p01] To fight an offensive war, the Confederacy purchased arms in Britain and converted British-built ships into commerce raiders, which targeted United States Merchant Marine ships in the Atlantic and Pacific oceans.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p01] The Confederacy smuggled 600,000 arms, enabling it to continue fighting for two more years.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p01] As insurance rates soared, American-flagged ships largely ceased traveling in international waters, though some were reflagged with European flags, which allowed them to continue operating.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p01] After the conclusion of the Civil War, the US government demanded Britain reimburse it for the damage caused by blockade runners and raiders outfitted in British ports.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p01] Britain paid the US$15 million in 1871, which covered costs associated with commerce raiding but nothing more.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p01] Although the Confederacy hoped Britain and France would join them against the Union, this was never likely, so they sought to bring them in as mediators.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p01] The Union worked to block this and threatened war against any country that recognized the Confederacy.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p01] In 1861, Southerners voluntarily embargoed cotton shipments, hoping to start an economic depression in Europe that would force Britain to enter the war, but this failed.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p01] Worse, Europe turned to Egypt and India for cotton, which they found superior, hindering the South's postwar recovery.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p01] Cotton diplomacy proved a failure, because Europe had a surplus of cotton, while the 1860–62 crop failures in Europe made the North's grain exports critically important.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p01] It also helped turn European opinion against the Confederacy.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p01] It was said that "King Corn was more powerful than King Cotton", as US grain increased from a quarter to almost half of British imports.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p01] Meanwhile, the war created jobs for arms makers, ironworkers, and ships to transport weapons.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p01] Lincoln's administration initially struggled to appeal to European public opinion.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p01] At first, diplomats explained that the US was not committed to ending slavery and emphasized legal arguments about the unconstitutionality of secession.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p01] Confederate representatives, however, focused on their struggle for liberty, commitment to free trade, and the essential role of cotton in the European economy.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p01] The European aristocracy was "absolutely gleeful in pronouncing the American debacle as proof that the entire experiment in popular government had failed.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p01] European government leaders welcomed the fragmentation of the ascendant American Republic." However, a European public with liberal sensibilities remained, which the US sought to appeal to by building connections with the international press.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p01] By 1861, Union diplomats like Carl Schurz realized emphasizing the war against slavery was the Union's most effective moral asset in swaying European public opinion.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p01] Seward was concerned an overly radical case for reunification would distress European merchants with cotton interests; even so, he supported a widespread campaign of public diplomacy.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p01] US minister to Britain Charles Francis Adams proved adept and convinced Britain not to challenge the Union blockade.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p01] The Confederacy purchased warships from commercial shipbuilders in Britain, with the most famous being the CSS *Alabama*, which caused considerable damage and led to serious postwar disputes.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p01] However, public opinion against slavery in Britain created a political liability for politicians, where the anti-slavery movement was powerful.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p01] War loomed in late 1861 between the US and Britain over the *Trent* Affair, which began when US Navy personnel boarded the British ship *Trent* and seized two Confederate diplomats.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p01] However, London and Washington smoothed this over after Lincoln released the two men.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p01] Prince Albert left his deathbed to issue diplomatic instructions to Lord Lyons during the *Trent* Affair.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p01] His request was honored, and, as a result, the British response to the US was toned down, helping avert war.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p01] In 1862, the British government considered mediating between the Union and Confederacy, though such an offer would have risked war with the US.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p01] British prime minister Lord Palmerston reportedly read *Uncle Tom's Cabin* three times when deciding what his decision would be.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p01] The Union victory at the Battle of Antietam caused the British to delay this decision.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p01] The Emancipation Proclamation increased the political liability of supporting the Confederacy.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p01] Realizing that Washington could not intervene in Mexico as long as the Confederacy controlled Texas, France invaded Mexico in 1861 and installed the Habsburg Austrian archduke Maximilian I as emperor.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p01] Washington repeatedly protested France's violation of the Monroe Doctrine.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p01] Despite sympathy for the Confederacy, France's seizure of Mexico deterred it from war with the Union.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p01] Confederate offers late in the war to end slavery in return for diplomatic recognition were not seriously considered by London or Paris.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p01] After 1863, the Polish revolt against Russia further distracted the European powers and ensured they remained neutral.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p01] Russia supported the Union, largely because it believed the US counterbalanced its geopolitical rival, the UK.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p01] In 1863, the Imperial Russian Navy's Baltic and Pacific fleets wintered in the American ports of New York and San Francisco, respectively.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p02] The Eastern theater refers to the military operations east of the Appalachian Mountains, including Virginia, West Virginia, Maryland, and Pennsylvania, the District of Columbia, and the coastal fortifications and seaports of North Carolina.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p02] McClellan took command of the Union Army of the Potomac on July 26, 1861, and the war began in earnest in 1862.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p02] Ohio forces would advance through Kentucky into Tennessee.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p02] The Missouri Department would drive south along the Mississippi River.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p02] The westernmost attack would originate from Kansas.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p02] The primary Confederate force in the Eastern theater was the Army of Northern Virginia.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p02] The Army originated as the (Confederate) Army of the Potomac, which was organized on June 20, 1861, from all operational forces in Northern Virginia.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p02] On July 20 and 21, the Army of the Shenandoah and forces from the District of Harpers Ferry were added.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p02] Units from the Army of the Northwest were merged into the Army of the Potomac between March 14 and May 17, 1862.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p02] The Army of the Potomac was renamed *Army of Northern Virginia* on March 14.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p02] The Army of the Peninsula was merged into it on April 12, 1862.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p02] When Virginia declared its secession in April 1861, Robert E.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p02] Lee chose to follow his home state, despite his desire for the country to remain intact and an offer of a senior Union command.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p02] In his four-volume biography of Lee published in 1934 and 1935, historian Douglas S.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p02] Freeman wrote that the army received its final name from Lee when he issued orders assuming command on June 1, 1862.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p02] However, Freeman wrote, Lee corresponded with Brigadier General Joseph E.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p02] Johnston, his predecessor in army command, before that date and referred to Johnston's command as the Army of Northern Virginia.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p02] Part of the confusion results from the fact that Johnston commanded the Department of Northern Virginia as of October 22, 1861, and the name Army of Northern Virginia was seen as an informal consequence of its parent department's name.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p02] Jefferson Davis and Johnston did not adopt the name, but the organization of units as of March 14 was clearly the same organization that Lee received on June 1, and is generally referred to as the Army of Northern Virginia, even if that is correct only in retrospect.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p02] On July 4 at Harper's Ferry, Colonel Thomas J.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p02] Jackson assigned Jeb Stuart command of all cavalry companies of the Army of the Shenandoah, and Jackson eventually commanded the Army of Northern Virginia's cavalry.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p02] Called the "Philippi Races" because of its brevity, Philippi, Virginia (now Philippi, WV) was the scene of the first organized land action of the American Civil War, on June 3, 1861.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p02] In July 1861, in the first in a series of prominent battles in the war, Union Army troops commanded by Maj.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p02] Irvin McDowell attacked Confederate forces, which were under the command of Beauregard near the national capital in Washington.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p02] The Confederacy repelled the attack in the First Battle of Bull Run.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p02] At the beginning of the battle, the Union appeared to hold the upper hand.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p02] The Union Army routed Confederate forces, then holding defensive positions, but Confederate reinforcements under Joseph E.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p02] Johnston arrived from the Shenandoah Valley by railroad, and the battle's course quickly changed.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p02] A brigade of Virginians, commanded by Thomas J.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p02] Jackson, then a relatively unknown brigadier general from Virginia Military Institute, stood its ground, leading to Jackson earning the nickname "Stonewall".
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p02] Lincoln urged the Union Army to commence offensive operations against Confederate forces, which led General George B.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p02] McClellan, in the spring of 1862, to attack Virginia by way of the peninsula between the York River and James River southeast of Richmond.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p02] McClellan's army reached the gates of Richmond in the Peninsula campaign.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p02] Also in the spring of 1862, in Shenandoah Valley, Jackson led his Valley Campaign, during which he employed rapid and unpredictable movements on interior lines.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p02] Jackson's 17,000 troops marched 646 miles (1,040 km) in 48 days, during which they won minor battles as they engaged three Union armies, comprising 52,000 men, including those of Nathaniel P.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p02] Frémont, preventing them from reinforcing the Union offensive against Richmond.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p02] The swiftness of Jackson's troops earned them the nickname foot cavalry.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p02] Johnston halted McClellan's advance at the Battle of Seven Pines, but he was wounded in the battle, and Robert E.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p02] Lee and his senior subordinates, James Longstreet and Stonewall Jackson, defeated McClellan in the Seven Days Battles, forcing McClellan's retreat.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p02] During the Northern Virginia Campaign, which included the Second Battle of Bull Run, Confederate forces registered another important military victory.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p02] McClellan resisted General-in-Chief Halleck's orders to send reinforcements to John Pope's Union Army of Virginia, which enabled Lee's Confederate forces to defeat twice the number of combined enemy troops.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p02] Emboldened by Second Bull Run, Confederate forces launched their first invasion of the North in the Maryland Campaign during which Lee led 45,000 Army of Northern Virginia troops across the Potomac River into Maryland on September 5.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p02] Lincoln then restored Pope's troops to McClellan, and McClellan and Lee clashed in the Battle of Antietam near Sharpsburg, Maryland, on September 17, 1862, which proved the bloodiest single day in both the Civil War and US military history.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p02] McClellan failed to respond in any measurable way to Lee's attempt to invade the North at Antietam, leading to his replacement by Maj.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p02] Burnside led Union Army troops in the Battle of Fredericksburg, where they were defeated on December 13, 1862.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p02] Over 12,000 Union soldiers were killed or wounded during futile attempts by Union troops to launch frontal assaults against Marye's Heights.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p02] After the battle, Burnside was replaced by Maj.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p02] Hooker, too, proved unable to defeat Lee's army; despite having more than twice as many troops as Lee, Hooker's Chancellorsville Campaign proved ineffective, and he was soundly defeated in the Battle of Chancellorsville, which was fought between April 30 and May 6, 1863.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p02] Chancellorsville is known as Lee's "perfect battle" because his risky decision to divide his army paid off.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p02] During the Battle of Chancellorsville, Stonewall Jackson was shot in his left arm and right hand by friendly fire, leading to the amputation of his arm, and he died of pneumonia.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p02] The fiercest fighting of the battle—and the second bloodiest day of the Civil War—occurred on May 3 as Lee launched multiple attacks against the Union position at Chancellorsville.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p02] That same day, John Sedgwick advanced across the Rappahannock River, defeated the small Confederate force at Marye's Heights in the Second Battle of Fredericksburg, and then moved westward, but Confederate forces succeeded in delaying Union forces in the Battle of Salem Church.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p02] George Meade during Lee's second invasion of the North, in June.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p02] In the Battle of Gettysburg, which proved the war's bloodiest and one of its most strategically significant, Meade defeated Lee in a three-day battle between July 1 and 3, 1863.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p02] The Battle of Gettysburg caused over 50,000 Union and Confederate casualties, but also proved the war's turning point, altering the course of the war in the Union's favor.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p02] Pickett's Charge, launched July 3, on the final day of the Battle of Gettysburg, is considered the high-water mark of the Confederacy, representing the collapse of any credible prospect that the Confederacy could prevail in the war.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p02] At Gettysburg, Lee's Army of Northern Virginia suffered 28,000 casualties versus Meade's 23,000, and Lee was repelled in a failed attempt to invade and occupy Union territory.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p02] The Western theater refers to military operations between the Appalachian Mountains and the Mississippi River, including Alabama, Georgia, Florida, Mississippi, North Carolina, Kentucky, South Carolina, Tennessee, and parts of Louisiana.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p02] The primary Union forces in this theater were the Army of the Tennessee and Army of the Cumberland, named for the two rivers, Tennessee River and Cumberland River.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p02] After Meade's inconclusive fall campaign, Lincoln turned to the Western theater for new leadership.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p02] At the same time, the Confederate stronghold of Vicksburg surrendered, giving the Union control of the Mississippi River, permanently isolating the western Confederacy, and producing the new leader Lincoln needed, Ulysses S.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p02] The Army of Tennessee, which served as the primary Confederate force in the Western theater, was formed on November 20, 1862, when General Braxton Bragg renamed the former Army of Mississippi.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p02] While Confederate forces had successes in the Eastern theater, they were defeated many times in the West.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p02] The Union's key strategist and tactician in the West was Ulysses S.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p02] Grant, who led the Union to victories in battles at Fort Henry (February 6, 1862) and Fort Donelson (February 11 to 16, 1862), earning him the nickname of "Unconditional Surrender" Grant.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p02] With these victories, the Union gained control of the Tennessee and Cumberland Rivers.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p02] Nathan Bedford Forrest rallied nearly 4,000 Confederate troops and led them to escape across the Cumberland River.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p02] Nashville and central Tennessee fell to the Union, leading to attrition of local food supplies and livestock and a breakdown in social organization.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p02] Confederate general Leonidas Polk subsequently invaded Columbus, Kentucky, which ended Kentucky's policy of neutrality and turned it against the Confederacy.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p02] Grant used river transport and Andrew Hull Foote's gunboats of the Western Flotilla, threatening the Confederacy's "Gibraltar of the West" in Columbus, Kentucky.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p02] Although rebuffed at Belmont, Grant cut off Columbus.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p02] Confederate forces, lacking their gunboats, were forced to retreat and the Union took control of west Kentucky and opened Tennessee in March 1862.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p02] At the Battle of Shiloh, in Shiloh, Tennessee, in April 1862, Confederate forces launched a surprise attack on Union forces, pushing them back to the Tennessee River as night fell.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p02] Over that night, however, the Navy landed reinforcements, and Grant counterattacked.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p02] Grant and the Union ultimately won a decisive victory in the first battle with a high number of casualties in what proved to be the first in a series of such battles.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p02] Confederate forces lost Albert Sidney Johnston, considered their finest general, before Lee emerged to assume command.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p02] One of the early Union objectives was to capture the Mississippi River, which would permit it to cut the Confederacy in half.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p02] The Mississippi was opened to Union traffic to the southern border of Tennessee after it took Island No.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p02] 10, New Madrid, Missouri, and then Memphis, Tennessee.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p02] In April 1862, the Union Navy captured New Orleans.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p02] "The key to the river was New Orleans, the South's largest port [and] greatest industrial center." US naval forces under Farragut ran past Confederate defenses south of New Orleans.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p02] Confederate forces abandoned the city, giving the Union a critical anchor in the deep South, which allowed Union forces to move up the Mississippi.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p02] Memphis fell to Union forces on June 6, 1862, allowing it to serve as a key base for further Union advances south along the Mississippi.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p02] On the Mississippi River, the Union took every fortress city with the exception of Vicksburg, Mississippi.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p02] But Confederate control of Vicksburg was sufficient in preventing the Union from controlling the entire river.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p02] Bragg's second invasion of Kentucky in the Confederate Heartland Offensive included initial successes, including Kirby Smith's triumph in the Battle of Richmond and the capture of the Kentucky capital of Frankfort, Kentucky, on September 3, 1862.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p02] The campaign ended with a meaningless victory over Maj.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p02] Don Carlos Buell at the Battle of Perryville, and Bragg was forced to end his attempt to invade and control Kentucky.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p02] Lacking logistical support and infantry recruits, Bragg was instead forced to retreat, and ended up being narrowly defeated by Maj.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p02] William Rosecrans in the Battle of Stones River in Tennessee in what proved to be the culmination of the Stones River Campaign.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p02] US naval forces assisted Grant in the long, complex Vicksburg Campaign, which resulted in Confederate forces surrendering in the Battle of Vicksburg in July 1863, which cemented Union control of the Mississippi River in one of the war's turning points.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p02] The one clear Confederate victory in the West was the Battle of Chickamauga.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p02] After Rosecrans' successful Tullahoma Campaign, Bragg, reinforced by Lt.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p02] James Longstreet's Corps, defeated Rosecrans, despite the defensive stand of Maj.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p02] Rosecrans retreated to Chattanooga, Tennessee, where Bragg was then besieged in the Chattanooga campaign.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p02] Grant marched to the relief of Rosecrans, where he led the defeat of Bragg in the Third Battle of Chattanooga, eventually causing Longstreet to abandon his Knoxville Campaign and driving Confederate forces out of Tennessee and opening a route to Atlanta and the heart of the Confederacy.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p02] The Trans-Mississippi theater refers to military operations west of the Mississippi, encompassing most of Missouri, Arkansas, most of Louisiana, and the Indian Territory in present-day Oklahoma.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p02] The Union's command was the Trans-Mississippi Division, or the Military Division of West Mississippi.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p02] The first major battle of the Trans-Mississippi theater was the Battle of Wilson's Creek (August 1861).
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p02] The Confederates were driven from Missouri early in the war as a result of the Battle of Pea Ridge.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p02] Extensive guerrilla warfare characterized the trans-Mississippi region, as the Confederacy lacked the troops and logistics to support regular armies that could challenge Union control.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p02] Roving Confederate bands such as Quantrill's Raiders terrorized the countryside, striking military installations and civilian settlements.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p02] The "Sons of Liberty" and "Order of the American Knights" attacked pro-Union people, elected officeholders, and unarmed uniformed soldiers.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p02] These partisans could not be driven out of Missouri, until an entire regular Union infantry division was engaged.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p02] By 1864, these violent activities harmed the nationwide antiwar movement organizing against the re-election of Lincoln.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p02] Missouri not only stayed in the Union, but Lincoln took 70 percent of the vote to win re-election.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p02] Small-scale military actions south and west of Missouri sought to control Indian Territory and New Mexico Territory for the Union.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p02] The Battle of Glorieta Pass was the decisive battle of the New Mexico Campaign.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p02] The Union repulsed Confederate incursions into New Mexico in 1862, and the exiled Arizona government withdrew into Texas.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p02] In the Indian Territory, civil war broke out within tribes.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p02] About 12,000 Indian warriors fought for the Confederacy but fewer for the Union.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p02] The most prominent Cherokee was Brigadier General Stand Watie, the last Confederate general to surrender.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p02] After the fall of Vicksburg in July 1863, Jefferson Davis informed General Kirby Smith in Texas that he could expect no further help from east of the Mississippi.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p02] Although he lacked resources to beat Union armies, he built up a formidable arsenal at Tyler, along with his own Kirby Smithdom economy, a virtual "independent fiefdom" in Texas, including railroad construction and international smuggling.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p02] The Union, in turn, did not directly engage him.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p02] The Union's 1864 Red River Campaign to take Shreveport, Louisiana, failed and Texas remained in Confederate hands throughout the war.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p02] The lower seaboard theater refers to military and naval operations that occurred near the coastal areas of the Southeast as well as the southern part of the Mississippi.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p02] Union naval activities were dictated by the Anaconda Plan.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p02] One of the earliest battles was fought in November 1861 at Port Royal Sound, south of Charleston.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p02] Much of the war along the South Carolina coast concentrated on capturing Charleston.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p02] In attempting to capture Charleston, the Union military tried two approaches: by land over James or Morris Islands or through the harbor.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p02] However, the Confederates were able to drive back each attack.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p02] A famous land attack was the Second Battle of Fort Wagner, in which the 54th Massachusetts Infantry took part.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p02] The Union suffered a serious defeat, losing 1,515 soldiers while the Confederates lost only 174.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p02] However, the 54th was hailed for its valor, which encouraged the general acceptance of the recruitment of African American soldiers into the Union Army, which reinforced the Union's numerical advantage.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p02] Fort Pulaski on the Georgia coast was an early target for the Union navy.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p02] Following the capture of Port Royal, an expedition was organized with engineer troops under the command of Captain Quincy Adams Gillmore, forcing a Confederate surrender.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p02] The Union army occupied the fort for the rest of the war after repairing it.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p02] In April 1862, a Union naval task force commanded by Commander David Dixon Porter attacked Forts Jackson and St.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p02] Philip, which guarded the river approach to New Orleans from the south.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p02] While part of the fleet bombarded the forts, other vessels forced a break in the obstructions in the river and enabled the rest of the fleet to steam upriver to the city.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p02] Benjamin Butler landed near the forts and forced their surrender.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p02] Butler's controversial command of New Orleans earned him the nickname "Beast".
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p02] The following year, the Union Army of the Gulf commanded by Maj.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p02] Banks laid siege to Port Hudson for nearly eight weeks, the longest siege in US military history.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p02] The Confederates attempted to defend with the Bayou Teche Campaign but surrendered after Vicksburg.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p02] These surrenders gave the Union control over the Mississippi.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p02] Several skirmishes but no major battles were fought in Florida.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p02] The biggest was the Battle of Olustee in early 1864.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p02] The Pacific coast theater refers to military operations on the Pacific Ocean and in the states and territories west of the Continental Divide.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p02] At the beginning of 1864, Lincoln made Grant commander of all Union armies.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p02] Grant made his headquarters with the Army of the Potomac and put Maj.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p02] William Tecumseh Sherman in command of most of the western armies.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p02] Grant understood the concept of total war and believed, along with Lincoln and Sherman, that only the utter defeat of Confederate forces and their economic base would end the war.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p02] This was total war not in killing civilians, but in injuring the Confederacy's capacity to produce and transport the supplies needed to continue the war.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p02] Sherman, at Grant's direction, seized provisions and destroyed homes, farms, and railroads, which Grant said "would otherwise have gone to the support of secession and rebellion.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p02] Grant devised a coordinated strategy that would strike at the entire Confederacy from multiple directions.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p02] Generals Meade and Benjamin Butler were ordered to move against Lee near Richmond, General Franz Sigel was to attack the Shenandoah Valley, General Sherman was to capture Atlanta and march to the Atlantic Ocean, Generals George Crook and William W.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p02] Averell were to operate against railroad supply lines in West Virginia, and Maj.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p02] Grant's army set out on the Overland Campaign intending to draw Lee into a defense of Richmond, where they would attempt to pin down and destroy the Confederate army.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p02] The Union army first attempted to maneuver past Lee and fought several battles, notably at the Wilderness, Spotsylvania, and Cold Harbor.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p02] These resulted in heavy losses on both sides and forced Lee's Confederates to fall back repeatedly.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p02] At the Battle of Yellow Tavern, the Confederates lost Jeb Stuart.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p02] An attempt to outflank Lee from the south failed under Butler, who was trapped inside the Bermuda Hundred river bend.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p02] Each battle resulted in setbacks for the Union that mirrored those they had suffered under prior generals, though unlike them, Grant chose to fight on rather than retreat.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p02] Grant was tenacious and kept pressing Lee's Army of Northern Virginia back to Richmond.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p02] While Lee was preparing for an attack on Richmond, Grant unexpectedly turned south to cross the James River and began the protracted Siege of Petersburg, where the two armies engaged in trench warfare for over nine months.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p02] To deny the Confederacy continued use of the Shenandoah Valley as a base from which to launch invasions of Maryland and the Washington area, and to threaten Lee's supply lines for his forces, Grant launched the Valley campaigns in May 1864.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p02] Sigel were repelled at the Battle of New Market by Confederate Gen.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p02] The Battle of New Market was the Confederacy's last major victory, and included a charge by teenage VMI cadets.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p02] After relieving Sigel, and following mixed performances by his successor, Grant finally found a commander, General Philip Sheridan, aggressive enough to prevail against the army of Maj.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p02] After a cautious start, Sheridan defeated Early in a series of battles in September and October 1864, including a decisive defeat at the Battle of Cedar Creek.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p02] Sheridan then proceeded through that winter to destroy the agricultural base of the Shenandoah Valley, a strategy similar to the tactics Sherman later employed in Georgia.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p02] Meanwhile, Sherman maneuvered from Chattanooga to Atlanta, defeating Confederate Generals Joseph E.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p02] The fall of Atlanta on September 2, 1864, guaranteed the reelection of Lincoln.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p02] Hood left the Atlanta area to swing around and menace Sherman's supply lines and invade Tennessee in the Franklin–Nashville Campaign.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p02] John Schofield defeated Hood at the Battle of Franklin, and George H.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p02] Thomas dealt Hood a massive defeat at the Battle of Nashville, effectively destroying Hood's army.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p02] Leaving Atlanta, and his base of supplies, Sherman's army marched, with no destination set, laying waste to about 20 percent of the farms in Georgia on his March to the Sea.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p02] He reached the Atlantic at Savannah, Georgia, in December 1864.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p02] Sherman's army was followed by thousands of freed slaves; there were no major battles along the march.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p02] Sherman turned north through South Carolina and North Carolina in his Carolinas campaign, to approach the Confederate Virginia lines from the south, increasing the pressure on Lee's army.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p02] Lee's army, thinned by desertion and casualties, was now much smaller than Grant's.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p02] One last Confederate attempt to break the Union hold on Petersburg failed at the decisive Battle of Five Forks on April 1.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p02] The Union now controlled the entire perimeter surrounding Richmond–Petersburg, completely cutting it off from the Confederacy.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p02] Realizing the capital was now lost, Lee's army and the Confederate government were forced to evacuate.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p02] The Confederate capital fell on April 2–3, to the Union XXV Corps, composed of black troops.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p02] The remaining Confederate units fled west after a defeat at Sayler's Creek on April 6.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p02] front page celebrated Lee's surrender, headlining how Grant let Confederate officers retain their sidearms and "paroled" the Confederate officers and men.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p02] News of Lee's April 9 surrender reached this southern newspaper (Savannah, Georgia) on April 15—after the April 14 shooting of President Lincoln.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p02] The article quotes Grant's terms of surrender.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p02] Lee did not intend to surrender, but planned to regroup at Appomattox Station, where supplies were to be waiting, and then continue the war.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p02] Grant chased Lee and got in front of him, so that when Lee's army reached the village of Appomattox Court House, they were surrounded.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p02] After an initial battle, Lee decided the fight was hopeless, and surrendered his Army of Northern Virginia to Grant on April 9, 1865, during a conference at the McLean House.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p02] In an untraditional gesture and as a sign of Grant's respect and anticipation of peacefully restoring Confederate states to the Union, Lee was permitted to keep his sword and horse, Traveller.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p02] His men were paroled, and a chain of Confederate surrenders began.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p02] On April 14, 1865, Lincoln was shot by John Wilkes Booth, a Confederate sympathizer.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p02] Lincoln's vice president, Andrew Johnson, was unharmed, because his would-be assassin, George Atzerodt, lost his nerve, so Johnson was immediately sworn in as president.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p02] Meanwhile, Confederate forces across the South surrendered, as news of Lee's surrender reached them.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p02] On April 26, the same day Sergeant Boston Corbett killed Booth at a tobacco barn, Johnston surrendered nearly 90,000 troops of the Army of Tennessee to Sherman at Bennett Place, near present-day Durham, North Carolina.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p02] It proved to be the largest surrender of Confederate forces.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p02] On May 4, all remaining Confederate forces in Alabama, Mississippi, and Louisiana east of the Mississippi, under the command of Lt.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p02] Confederate president Davis was captured in retreat at Irwinville, Georgia on May 10.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p02] The final land battle was fought on May 13, 1865, at the Battle of Palmito Ranch in Texas.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p02] Buckner, acting for Edmund Smith, signed a military convention surrendering Confederate forces in the Trans-Mississippi Department.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p02] This date is often cited by contemporaries and historians as the effective end date of the war.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p02] On June 2, with most of his troops having already gone home, a reluctant Kirby Smith had little choice but to sign the official surrender document.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p02] General Stand Watie became the last Confederate general to surrender his forces.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p02] Gordon Granger announced General Order No.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p02] 3, bringing the Emancipation Proclamation into effect in Texas and freeing the last slaves of the Confederacy.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p02] The anniversary of this date is now celebrated as Juneteenth.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p02] The naval part of the war ended more slowly.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p02] Britain finally responded on June 6, by transmitting a letter from Foreign Secretary John Russell, 1st Earl Russell, to the Lords of the Admiralty withdrawing rights to Confederate warships to enter British ports and waters.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p02] US Secretary of State Seward welcomed the withdrawal of concessions to the Confederates.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p02] Finally, on October 18, Russell advised the Admiralty that the time specified in his June message had elapsed and "all measures of a restrictive nature on vessels of war of the United States in British ports, harbors, and waters, are now to be considered as at an end".
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p02] Nonetheless, the final Confederate surrender was in Liverpool, England where James Iredell Waddell, the captain of CSS *Shenandoah*, surrendered the cruiser to British authorities on November 6.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p02] Legally, the war did not end until August 20, 1866, when President Johnson issued a proclamation that declared "that the said insurrection is at an end and that peace, order, tranquillity, and civil authority now exist in and throughout the whole of the United States of America".
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p02] The causes of the war, reasons for its outcome, and even its name are subjects of lingering contention.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p02] The North and West grew wealthy while the once-rich South became poor for a century.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p02] The national political power of the slaveowners and rich Southerners ended.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p02] Historians are less sure about the results of postwar Reconstruction, especially regarding the second-class citizenship of the freedmen and their poverty.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p02] Historians have debated whether the Confederacy could have won the war.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p02] McPherson, argue Confederate victory was possible.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p02] McPherson argues that the North's advantage in population and resources made Northern victory likely, but not guaranteed.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p02] He argues that if the Confederacy had fought using unconventional tactics, it would have more easily been able to hold out long enough to exhaust the Union.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p02] Confederates did not need to invade and hold enemy territory to win, but only to fight a defensive war to convince the North the cost of winning was too high.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p02] The North needed to conquer and hold vast stretches of enemy territory and defeat Confederate armies to win.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p02] Lincoln was not a military dictator and could fight only as long as the American public supported the war.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p02] The Confederacy sought to win independence by outlasting Lincoln; however, after Atlanta fell and Lincoln defeated McClellan in the election of 1864, hope for a political victory for the South ended.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p02] Lincoln had secured the support of the Republicans, War Democrats, border states, emancipated slaves, and the neutrality of Britain and France.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p02] By defeating the Democrats and McClellan, he defeated the Copperheads, who had wanted a negotiated peace with the Confederacy.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p02] Some scholars argue the Union held an insurmountable long-term advantage over the Confederacy in industrial strength and population.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p02] Confederate actions, they argue, only delayed defeat.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p02] A minority view among historians is that the Confederacy lost because, as E.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p02] Merton Coulter put it, "people did not will hard enough and long enough to win".
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p02] However, most historians reject the argument.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p02] McPherson, after reading thousands of letters written by Confederate soldiers, found strong patriotism that continued to the end; they truly believed they were fighting for freedom and liberty.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p02] Even as the Confederacy was visibly collapsing in 1864–65, most Confederate soldiers were fighting hard.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p02] Also important were Lincoln's eloquence in articulating the national purpose and his skill in keeping the border states committed to the Union cause.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p02] The Emancipation Proclamation was an effective use of the president's war powers.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p02] The Confederate government failed to get Europe involved militarily.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p02] Southern leaders needed to get European powers to help break the blockade the Union had created around Southern ports.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p02] Lincoln's naval blockade was 95 percent effective at stopping trade goods; as a result, imports and exports to the South declined significantly.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p02] The abundance of European cotton and Britain's hostility to slavery, along with Lincoln's naval blockades, severely decreased any chance that Britain or France would enter the war.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p02] Doyle has argued that the Union victory had a major impact on world history.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p02] The Union victory energized popular democratic forces.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p02] A Confederate victory, on the other hand, would have meant a new birth of slavery, not of freedom.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p02] Scholars have debated what the effects of the war were on political and economic power in the South.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p02] The prevailing view is that the southern planter elite retained its powerful position in the South.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p02] However, a 2017 study challenges this, noting that while some Southern elites retained their economic status, the turmoil of the 1860s created greater opportunities for economic mobility in the South, than in the North.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p02] Exact casualty figures were collected for the Union, but Confederate records were poorly kept, or lost in the chaos of defeat.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p02] Thus, the casualty figures are imprecise and based on statistical extrapolation.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p02] Neither side kept a tally of civilian deaths due to the war.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p02] In the 19th century, the death toll had been estimated at a lower 620,000.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p02] In 2011, the death toll was recalculated based on a 1% sample of census data, yielding approximately 750,000 soldier deaths, 20 percent higher than traditionally estimated, and possibly as high as 850,000.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p02] The figure was recalculated to 698,000 soldier deaths in 2024 after examining newly available full census records.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p02] Mortality rates among men were as high as 19 percent in Louisiana, and 16.6–16.7 percent in Georgia and South Carolina respectively.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p02] The war resulted in at least 1,030,000 casualties (3 percent of the population), including an estimated 698,000 soldier deaths—two-thirds by disease.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p02] Based on 1860 census figures, 8 percent of all white men aged 13–43 died in the war, including 6 percent in the North and 18 percent in the South.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p02] About 56,000 soldiers died in prison camps during the War.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p02] An estimated 60,000 soldiers lost limbs.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p02] As McPherson notes, the war's "cost in American lives was as great as in all of the nation's other wars combined through Vietnam".
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p02] In addition, there were 4,523 deaths in the Navy (2,112 in battle) and 460 in the Marines (148 in battle).
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p02] The US Colored Troops made up 10 percent of the Union death toll—15 percent of Union deaths from disease and less than 3 percent of those killed in battle.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p02] Losses among African Americans were high.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p02] In the last year and a half and from all reported casualties, approximately 20 percent of all African Americans enrolled in the military died during the war.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p02] Their mortality rate was significantly higher than white soldiers.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p02] While 15 percent of US Volunteers and just 9 percent of white Regular Army troops died, 21 percent of US Colored Troops died.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p02] While the figures of 360,000 army deaths for the Union and 260,000 for the Confederacy remained commonly cited, they are incomplete.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p02] This often happened only days or weeks later.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p02] Francis Amasa Walker, superintendent of the 1870 census, used census and surgeon general data to estimate a minimum of 500,000 Union military deaths and 350,000 Confederate military deaths, a total of 850,000 soldiers.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p02] While Walker's estimates were originally dismissed because of the 1870 census's undercounting, it was later found that the census was only off by 6.5 percent and that the data Walker used would be roughly accurate.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p02] Losses were far higher than during the war with Mexico, which saw roughly 13,000 American deaths, including fewer than two thousand killed in battle, between 1846 and 1848.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p02] One reason for the high number of battle deaths in the civil war was the continued use of tactics similar to those of the Napoleonic Wars, such as charging.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p02] With the advent of more accurate rifled barrels, Minié balls, and (near the end of the war for the Union) repeating firearms such as the Spencer repeating rifle and the Henry repeating rifle, soldiers were mowed down when standing in lines in the open.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p02] This led to the adoption of trench warfare, a style of fighting that defined much of World War I.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p02] Deaths among former slaves has proven hard to estimate, due to the lack of reliable census data, though they were known to be considerable, as former slaves were set free or escaped in massive numbers in areas where the Union army did not have sufficient shelter, doctors, or food for them.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p02] Professor Jim Downs states that tens of thousands to hundreds of thousands of slaves died during the war from disease, starvation, or exposure, and that if these deaths are counted in the war's total, the death toll would exceed 1 million.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p02] It is estimated that during the war, of the equines killed, including horses, mules, donkeys and even confiscated children's ponies, over 32,600 of them belonged to the Union and 45,800 the Confederacy.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p02] However, other estimates place the total at 1,000,000.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p02] It is estimated that 544 Confederate flags were captured during the war by the Union.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p02] The flags were sent to the War Department in Washington.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p02] The Union flags captured by the Confederates were sent to Richmond.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p02] Abolishing slavery was not a Union war goal from the outset but quickly became one.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p02] Lincoln initially claimed that preserving the Union was the central goal.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p02] In contrast, the South fought to preserve slavery.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p02] While not all Southerners saw themselves as fighting for slavery, most officers and over a third of the rank and file in Lee's army had close family ties to slavery.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p02] To Northerners, the motivation was primarily to preserve the Union, not to abolish slavery.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p02] Lincoln's decision to issue the Proclamation angered Peace Democrats ("Copperheads") and War Democrats, but energized most Republicans.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p02] By warning that free blacks would flood the North, Democrats made gains in the 1862 elections, but they did not gain control of Congress.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p02] The Republicans' counterargument that slavery was the mainstay of the enemy steadily gained support, with the Democrats losing decisively in the 1863 elections in the Northern state of Ohio, when they tried to resurrect anti-black sentiment.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p02] The Emancipation Proclamation legally freed the slaves in states "in rebellion", but, as a practical matter, slavery for the 3.5 million black people in the South effectively ended in each area when Union armies arrived.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p02] The last Confederate slaves were freed on June 19, 1865, celebrated as the modern holiday of Juneteenth.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p02] Slaves in the border states and those in some former Confederate territory occupied before the Emancipation Proclamation were freed by state action or (on December 6, 1865) by the Thirteenth Amendment.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p02] The Emancipation Proclamation enabled African Americans, both free blacks and escaped slaves, to join the Union Army.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p02] About 190,000 volunteered, further enhancing the numerical advantage the Union armies enjoyed over the Confederates, who did not dare emulate the equivalent manpower source for fear of undermining the legitimacy of slavery.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p02] During the war, sentiment concerning slaves, enslavement, and emancipation in the United States was divided.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p02] Lincoln's fears of making slavery a war issue were based on a harsh reality: abolition did not enjoy wide support in the west, the territories, and the border states.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p02] In 1861, Lincoln worried that premature attempts at emancipation would mean the loss of the border states, and that "to lose Kentucky is nearly the same as to lose the whole game".
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p02] Copperheads and some War Democrats opposed emancipation, although the latter eventually accepted it as part of the total war needed to save the Union.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p02] Lincoln reversed attempts at emancipation by Secretary of War Simon Cameron and Generals John C.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p02] Frémont and David Hunter, in an effort to retain the loyalty of the border states and the War Democrats.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p02] Lincoln warned the border states that a more radical type of emancipation would happen if they rejected his plan of gradual compensated emancipation and voluntary colonization.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p02] But compensated emancipation occurred only in the District of Columbia, where Congress had the power to enact it.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p02] When Lincoln told his cabinet about his proposed emancipation proclamation, which would apply to the states still in rebellion on January 1, 1863, Seward advised Lincoln to wait for a Union military victory before issuing it, because to do otherwise would seem like "our last shriek on the retreat".
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p02] Walter Stahr, however, writes, "There are contemporary sources, however, that suggest others were involved in the decision to delay", and Stahr quotes them.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p02] , who were fugitive slaves, including cooks, laundresses, laborers, teamsters, railroad repair crews, fled to the Union Army, but were not legally freed until the Emancipation Proclamation, which Lincoln signed on January 1, 1863, more than two years before the end of the Civil War.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p02] ; seen here are black and white teenaged soldiers who volunteered to fight for the Union.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p02] Lincoln laid the groundwork for public support in an open letter published in response to Horace Greeley's "The Prayer of Twenty Millions"; the letter stated that Lincoln's goal was to save the Union, and that, if he freed the slaves, it would be as a means to that end.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p02] He also had a meeting at the White House with five African American representatives on August 14, 1862.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p02] Arranging for a reporter to be present, he urged his visitors to agree to the voluntary colonization of black people.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p02] Lincoln's motive for both his letter to Greeley and his statement to the black visitors was apparently to make his forthcoming Emancipation Proclamation more palatable to racist white people.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p02] A Union victory in the Battle of Antietam on September 17, 1862, provided Lincoln with an opportunity to issue the preliminary Emancipation Proclamation, and the War Governors' Conference added support for the proclamation.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p02] Lincoln issued his preliminary Emancipation Proclamation on September 22, 1862.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p02] It stated that slaves in all states in rebellion on January 1, 1863, would be free.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p02] He issued his final Emancipation Proclamation on January 1, 1863, keeping his promise.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p02] Hodges, Lincoln explained his belief that "If slavery is not wrong, nothing is wrong....
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p02] And yet I have never understood that the Presidency conferred upon me an unrestricted right to act officially upon this judgment and feeling....
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p02] Lincoln's moderate approach succeeded in inducing the border states to remain in the Union and War Democrats to support the Union.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p02] The border states, which included Kentucky, Missouri, Maryland, Delaware, and Union-controlled regions around New Orleans, Norfolk, Virginia, and elsewhere, were not covered by the Emancipation Proclamation.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p02] Nor was Tennessee, which had come under Union control.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p02] Missouri and Maryland abolished slavery on their own; Kentucky and Delaware did not.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p02] Still, the proclamation did not enjoy universal support.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p02] It caused much unrest in what were then considered western states, where racist sentiments led to a great fear of abolition.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p02] There was some concern that the proclamation would lead to the secession of western states, and its issuance prompted the stationing of Union troops in Illinois in case of rebellion.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p02] Since the Emancipation Proclamation was based on the president's war powers, it applied only in territory held by Confederates at the time it was issued.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p02] However, the Proclamation became a symbol of the Union's growing commitment to add emancipation to the Union's definition of liberty.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p02] The Emancipation Proclamation greatly reduced the Confederacy's hope of being recognized or otherwise aided by Britain or France.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p02] By late 1864, Lincoln was playing a leading role in getting the House of Representatives to vote for the Thirteenth Amendment, which mandated the ending of chattel slavery.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p03] The war devastated the South and posed serious questions of how it would be reintegrated into the Union.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p03] The war destroyed much of the South's wealth, in part because wealth held in enslaved people (at least $1,000 each for a healthy adult prior to the war) was wiped off the books.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p03] All accumulated investment in Confederate bonds was forfeited; most banks and railroads were bankrupt.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p03] The income per person dropped to less than 40 percent of that of the North, and that lasted into the 20th century.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p03] Southern influence in the federal government, previously considerable, was greatly diminished until the second half of the 20th century.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p03] Reconstruction began during the war, with the Emancipation Proclamation of January 1863, and it continued until 1877.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p03] From the Union perspective, the goals of Reconstruction were to consolidate victory by reuniting the Union, to guarantee a "republican form of government" for the ex-Confederate states, and to permanently end slavery—and prevent semi-slavery status.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p03] President Johnson, who took office in April 1865, took a lenient approach and saw the achievement of the main war goals as realized in 1865, when each ex-rebel state repudiated secession and ratified the Thirteenth Amendment.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p03] Radical Republicans demanded proof that Confederate nationalism was dead and that the slaves were truly free.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p03] They overrode Johnson's vetoes of civil rights legislation, and the House impeached him, although the Senate did not convict him.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p03] In 1868 and 1872, the Republican candidate Grant won the presidency.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p03] In 1872, the "Liberal Republicans" argued that the war goals had been achieved and Reconstruction should end.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p03] They chose Horace Greeley to head a presidential ticket in 1872 but were decisively defeated.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p03] In 1874, Democrats, primarily Southern, took control of Congress and opposed further reconstruction.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p03] The Compromise of 1877 closed with a national consensus, except on the part of former slaves, that the war had finally ended.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p03] With the withdrawal of federal troops, however, white men retook control of every Southern legislature, and the Jim Crow era of disenfranchisement and legal segregation was ushered in.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p03] The war had a demonstrable impact on American politics.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p03] Many veterans on both sides were elected to political office, including five US presidents: Ulysses Grant, Rutherford B.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p03] Garfield, Benjamin Harrison, and William McKinley.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p03] The war is a central event in American collective memory.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p03] There are innumerable statues, commemorations, books, and archival collections.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p03] The memory includes the home front, military affairs, the treatment of soldiers, both living and dead, in the war's aftermath, depictions of the war in literature and art, evaluations of heroes and villains, and considerations of the moral and political lessons of the war.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p03] The last theme includes moral evaluations of racism and slavery, heroism and cowardice in combat and behind the lines, and issues of democracy and minority rights, as well as the notion of an "Empire of Liberty" influencing the world.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p03] Historians have paid great attention to the causes of the war as well as to the war itself.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p03] Military history has developed outside as well as inside academia, leading to a proliferation of studies by non-scholars who nevertheless are familiar with the primary sources and pay close attention to battles and campaigns and who write for the general public.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p03] Practically every major figure in the war, both North and South, has had a serious biographical study.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p03] Even the name used for the conflict has been controversial, with many names used for it.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p03] During and immediately after the war, Northern historians often used a term like "War of the Rebellion".
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p03] Writers in rebel states often referred to the "War for Southern Independence".
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p03] Some Southerners have described it as the "War of Northern Aggression".
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p03] The memory of the war in the white South crystallized in the myth of the "Lost Cause": that the Confederate cause was just and heroic.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p03] The myth shaped regional identity and race relations for generations.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p03] Nolan notes that the Lost Cause was expressly a rationalization, a cover-up to vindicate the name and fame of those in rebellion.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p03] Some claims revolve around the insignificance of slavery as a cause; some appeals highlight cultural differences between North and South; the military conflict by Confederate actors is idealized; in any case, secession was said to be lawful.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p03] Nolan argues that the adoption of the Lost Cause perspective facilitated the reunification of the North and the South while excusing the "virulent racism" of the 19th century, sacrificing black American progress to white man's reunification.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p03] He also deems the Lost Cause "a caricature of the truth.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p03] This caricature wholly misrepresents and distorts the facts of the matter" in every instance.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p03] The Lost Cause myth was formalized by Charles A.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p03] Beard, whose *The Rise of American Civilization* (1927) spawned Beardian historiography.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p03] The Beards downplayed slavery, abolitionism, and issues of morality.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p03] Though this interpretation was abandoned by the Beards in the 1940s, and by historians generally by the 1950s, Beardian themes still echo among Lost Cause writers.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p03] The first efforts at Civil War battlefield preservation and memorialization came during the war, with the establishment of National Cemeteries at Gettysburg, Mill Springs and Chattanooga.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p03] Soldiers began erecting markers on battlefields beginning with the First Battle of Bull Run in 1861.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p03] The oldest surviving monument is the Hazen Brigade Monument near Murfreesboro in Central Tennessee, built in the summer of 1863 by soldiers in Union Col.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p03] Hazen's brigade to mark the spot where they buried their dead, following the Battle of Stones River.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p03] The Shiloh National Military Park was established in 1894 in Shiloh, Tennessee, followed by the Gettysburg National Military Park in 1895, and Vicksburg National Military Park in 1899.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p03] In 1933, these five parks and other national monuments were transferred to the National Park Service.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p03] Chief among modern efforts to preserve Civil War sites has been the American Battlefield Trust, with more than 130 battlefields in 24 states.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p03] The five major battlefield parks operated by the National Park Service had a combined 3 million visitors in 2018, down 70% from 10 million in 1970.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p03] The Civil War has been commemorated in many ways, ranging from the reenactment of battles, to statues and memorial halls being erected, to films, and to stamps and coins with Civil War themes being issued, all of which helped to shape public memory.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p03] These commemorations occurred in greater numbers on the 100th and 150th anniversaries of the war.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p03] Hollywood's take on the war has been especially influential in shaping public memory, as in such film classics as *The Birth of a Nation* (1915), *Gone with the Wind* (1939), and *Lincoln* (2012).
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p03] Ken Burns's PBS television series *The Civil War* (1990) is well-remembered, though criticized for its historical inaccuracy.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p03] Technological innovations during the war had a great impact on 19th-century science.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p03] The war was an early example of an "industrial war", in which technological might is used to achieve military supremacy.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p03] New inventions, such as the train and telegraph, delivered soldiers, supplies and messages at a time when horses had been the fastest way to travel.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p03] It was also in this war that aerial warfare, in the form of reconnaissance balloons, was first used.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p03] It saw the first action involving steam-powered ironclad warships in naval warfare history.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p03] Repeating firearms such as the Henry rifle, Spencer repeating rifle, Colt revolving rifle, Triplett & Scott carbine and others, first appeared during the Civil War; they were a revolutionary invention that would soon replace muzzle-loading and single-shot firearms.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p03] The war saw the first appearances of rapid-firing weapons and machine guns such as the Agar gun and Gatling gun.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p03] The Civil War is one of the most studied events in American history, and the collection of cultural works around it is enormous.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/american-civil-war-p03] This section gives an abbreviated overview of the most notable works.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/area-codes-843-and-854] Area code 843 entered service on March 22, 1998, created in a split of area code 803.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/area-codes-843-and-854] In 2013, the NANP Administrator determined that 843 would run out of central office prefixes in 2015.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/area-codes-843-and-854] In addition to the rapid growth of the Grand Strand, Charleston and Beaufort/Hilton Head areas, most of the southern portion of the numbering plan area is part of the Savannah, Georgia LATA.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/area-codes-843-and-854] On December 9, 2013, it was decided that the 843 territory would receive the state's first all-service overlay.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/area-codes-843-and-854] On December 16, 2013, the new area code of 854, approved by the South Carolina Public Service Commission, was announced.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/area-codes-843-and-854] Permissive dialing continued until September 18, 2015, during which both seven- and ten-digit dialing were supported.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/area-codes-843-and-854] On September 19, 2015, ten-digit dialing became mandatory in the 843/854 territory.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/area-codes-843-and-854] The first new 854 numbers were issued sometime in the fall of 2015.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/area-codes-843-and-854] Major cities within the area code are in bold.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/asian-americans-p01] Although this term had historically been used for all the indigenous peoples of the continent of Asia, the usage of the term "Asian" by the U.S.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/asian-americans-p01] Census Bureau denotes a racial category that includes people with origins or ancestry from Central Asia, East Asia, South Asia, and Southeast Asia.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/asian-americans-p01] It excludes people with ethnic origins from West Asia, who were historically classified as "white" and proposed to be categorized as Middle Eastern Americans starting from the 2030 census.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/asian-americans-p01] Central Asian ancestries (including Kazakh, Kyrgyz, Tajik, Turkmen, and Uzbek) were previously not included in any racial category but have been designated as "Asian" as of 2024.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/asian-americans-p01] It is also explicitly stated on the Census that racial categories reflect social definitions of race based on the American general public.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/asian-americans-p01] They are not meant to define race biologically, anthropologically or genetically.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/asian-americans-p01] The "Asian" census category includes people who indicate their race(s) on the census as "Asian" or reported entries such as "Chinese, Indian, Bangladeshi, Filipino, Vietnamese, Indonesian, Korean, Japanese, Pakistani, Thai, and Other Asian".
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/asian-americans-p01] In 2020, Americans who identified as Asian alone (19,886,049) or in combination with other races (4,114,949) made up 7.2% of the US population.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/asian-americans-p01] Chinese, Indian, and Filipino Americans make up the largest share of the Asian American population with 5.5 million, 5.2 million, and 4.6 million people respectively.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/asian-americans-p01] These numbers equal 23%, 20%, and 18% of the total Asian American population, or 1.5%, 1.2%, and 1.2% of the total US population.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/asian-americans-p01] Vietnamese Americans are the 4th largest Asian American population, and Korean Americans are the 5th largest with both populations making up 8% of the Asian American population respectively.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/asian-americans-p01] Although migrants from Asia have been in parts of the contemporary United States since the 17th century, large-scale immigration did not begin until the mid-19th century.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/asian-americans-p01] Nativist immigration laws during the 1880s–1920s excluded various Asian groups, eventually prohibiting almost all Asian immigration to the continental United States.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/asian-americans-p01] After immigration laws were reformed during the 1940s–1960s, abolishing national origins quotas, Asian immigration increased rapidly.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/asian-americans-p01] Analyses of the 2010 census have shown that, by percentage change, Asian Americans are the fastest-growing racial group in the United States.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/asian-americans-p01] As with other racial and ethnicity-based terms, formal and common usage have changed markedly through the short history of this term.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/asian-americans-p01] Prior to the late 1960s, people of various Asian ancestries were usually referred to as *Yellow*, *Oriental*, *Asiatic*, *Brown*, *Mongoloid*, or *Hindoo*.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/asian-americans-p01] This effort was part of New Left anti-war and anti-imperialist activism, directly opposing what was viewed as an unjust Vietnam War.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/asian-americans-p01] Prior to being included in the "Asian" category in the 1980s, many Americans of South Asian descent usually classified themselves as *Caucasian* or *other*.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/asian-americans-p01] Changing patterns of immigration and an extensive period of exclusion of Asian immigrants have resulted in demographic changes that have in turn affected the formal and common understandings of what defines Asian American.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/asian-americans-p01] For example, since the removal of restrictive "national origins" quotas in 1965, the Asian American population has diversified greatly to include more of the peoples with ancestry from various parts of Asia.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/asian-americans-p01] Today, "Asian American" is the accepted term for most formal purposes, such as government and academic research, although it is often shortened to *Asian* in common usage.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/asian-americans-p01] The most commonly used definition of Asian American is the US Census Bureau definition, which includes all people with origins in East Asia, South Asia, and Southeast Asia.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/asian-americans-p01] This is chiefly because the census definitions determine many governmental classifications, notably for equal opportunity programs and measurements.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/asian-americans-p01] According to the Oxford English Dictionary, "Asian person" in the United States is most often thought of as a person of East Asian descent.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/asian-americans-p01] In vernacular usage, "Asian" is usually used to refer to those of East or Southeast Asian descent, with South Asians not included as often.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/asian-americans-p01] This differs from the US census definition, and the Asian American Studies departments in many universities consider all those of East, South, or Southeast Asian descent to be "Asian".
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/asian-americans-p01] As such, "Asian" and "African" ancestry are seen as racial categories only for the purpose of the census, with the definition referring to ancestry from parts of the Asian and African continents outside of parts of West Asia and North Africa.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/asian-americans-p01] In 1980 and before, census forms listed particular Asian ancestries as separate groups, along with *white* and *black or negro*.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/asian-americans-p01] Asian Americans had also been classified as "other".
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/asian-americans-p01] In 1977, the federal Office of Management and Budget issued a directive requiring government agencies to maintain statistics on racial groups, including on "Asian or Pacific Islander".
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/asian-americans-p01] By the 1990 census, "Asian or Pacific Islander (API)" was included as an explicit category, although respondents had to select one particular ancestry as a subcategory.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/asian-americans-p01] Beginning with the 2000 census, two separate categories were used: "Asian American" and "Native Hawaiian and Other Pacific Islander".
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/asian-americans-p01] The definition of *Asian American* has variations that derive from the use of the word *American* in different contexts.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/asian-americans-p01] Immigration status, citizenship (by birthright and by naturalization), acculturation, and language ability are some variables that are used to define *American* for various purposes and may vary in formal and everyday usage.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/asian-americans-p01] For example, restricting *American* to include only US citizens conflicts with discussions of Asian American businesses, which generally refer both to citizen and non-citizen owners.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/asian-americans-p01] A 2023 Pew Research Center survey of Asian Americans found that 28% self-identify as "Asian", with 52% preferring to refer to themselves by more specific ethnic groupings and 10% simply self-identifying as "American".
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/asian-americans-p01] In a PBS interview from 2004, a panel of Asian American writers discussed how some groups include people of Middle Eastern descent in the Asian American category.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/asian-americans-p01] The majority of Asian Americans feel ambivalence about the term "Asian American" as a term by which to identify themselves.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/asian-americans-p01] Pyong Gap Min, a sociologist and Professor of Sociology at Queens College, has stated the term is merely political, used by Asian American activists and further reinforced by the government.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/asian-americans-p01] Beyond that, he feels that South Asians and East Asians do not have commonalities in "culture, physical characteristics, or pre-migrant historical experiences".
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/asian-americans-p01] Scholars have grappled with the accuracy, correctness, and usefulness of the term Asian American.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/asian-americans-p01] The term "Asian" in Asian American most often comes under fire for only encompassing some of the diverse peoples of Asia, and for being considered a racial category instead of a non-racial "ethnic" category.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/asian-americans-p01] This is namely due to the categorization of the racially different South Asians and East Asians as part of the same "race".
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/asian-americans-p01] Furthermore, it has been noted that West Asians (whom are not considered "Asian" under the US census) share some cultural similarities with Indians but very little with East Asians, with the latter two groups being classified as "Asian".
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/asian-americans-p01] Scholars have also found it difficult to determine why Asian Americans are considered a "race" while Americans of Hispanic and Latino heritage are a non-racial "ethnic group", given how the category of Asian Americans similarly comprises people with diverse origins.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/asian-americans-p01] However, it has been argued that South Asians and East Asians can be "justifiably" grouped together because of Buddhism's origins in South Asia and contemporary practice in East Asia.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/asian-americans-p01] In contrast, leading social sciences and humanities scholars of race and Asian American identity point out that because of the racial constructions in the United States, including the social attitudes toward race and those of Asian ancestry, Asian Americans have a "shared racial experience".
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/asian-americans-p01] Because of this shared experience, the term Asian American is argued as still being a useful panethnic category because of the similarity of some experiences among Asian Americans, including stereotypes specific to people in this category.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/asian-americans-p01] Despite this, others have stated that many Americans do not treat all Asian Americans equally, highlighting the fact that "Asian American" is generally synonymous with people of East Asian descent, thereby excluding people of Southeast Asian and South Asian origin.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/asian-americans-p01] Some South and Southeast Asian Americans may not identify with the Asian American label, instead describing themselves as "Brown Asians" or simply "Brown", due to the perceived racial and cultural differences between them and East Asian Americans.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/asian-americans-p01] The demographics of Asian Americans describe a heterogeneous group of people in the United States who can trace their ancestry to one or more countries in Central, East, South, or Southeast Asia.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/asian-americans-p01] Because they compose 7.3% of the entire US population, the diversity of the group is often disregarded in media and news discussions of "Asians" or of "Asian Americans".
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/asian-americans-p01] While there are some commonalities across ethnic subgroups, there are significant differences among different Asian ethnicities that are related to each group's history.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/asian-americans-p01] The Asian American population is greatly urbanized, with nearly three-quarters of them living in metropolitan areas with population greater than 2.5 million.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/asian-americans-p01] As of July 2015, California had the largest population of Asian Americans of any state, and Hawaii was the only state where Asian Americans were the majority of the population.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/asian-americans-p01] This grouping is by country of origin before immigration to the United States, and not necessarily by ethnicity, as for example (nonexclusive), Singaporean and Malaysian Americans may be of Malay, Chinese, or Indian descent.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/asian-americans-p01] Asian Americans include **multiracial or mixed race** persons with origins or ancestry in both the above groups and another race, or multiple of the above groups.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/asian-americans-p01] In 2020, 1.2% of the US population identified as multiracial Asian, with this group making up over 16% of the Asian American population.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/asian-americans-p01] As of 2023, a recent survey showed one out of five respondents said they do not identify as Asian to non-Asians.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/asian-americans-p01] Most immigrants identify as Asian compared to American-born Asian Americans.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/asian-americans-p01] People under the age 18 are more likely not to identify as Asian.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/asian-americans-p01] People over the age of 65 are more likely to identify as Asian.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/asian-americans-p01] In 2010, there were 2.8 million people (age 5 and older) who spoke one of the Chinese languages at home; after the Spanish language, it is the third most common language in the United States.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/asian-americans-p01] Other sizable Asian languages, are Tagalog, Vietnamese, and Korean, with all four having more than 1 million speakers in the United States.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/asian-americans-p01] Election materials were also available in Gujarati, Japanese, Khmer, Korean, and Thai.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/asian-americans-p01] A 2013 poll found that 48 percent of Asian Americans considered media in their native language as their primary news source.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/asian-americans-p01] The 2000 census found the more prominent languages of the Asian American community to include the Chinese languages (Cantonese, Taishanese, and Hokkien), Tagalog, Vietnamese, Korean, Japanese, Hindi, Urdu, Telugu, and Gujarati.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/asian-americans-p01] In 2008, the Chinese, Japanese, Korean, Tagalog, and Vietnamese languages are all used in elections in Alaska, California, Hawaii, Illinois, New York, Texas, and Washington state.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/asian-americans-p01] According to a Gallup survey conducted from June to September 2012, 4.3% of Asian Americans self-identify as LGBT, compared to 3.4% of the general American population.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/asian-americans-p01] This makes the Asian-American population disproportionately over-represented within the LGBT community.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/asian-americans-p01] In a Gallup survey conducted in 2017, 4.9 percent of Asian Americans identified as LGBT, representing the second-highest growth of LGBT representation in the United States, behind Hispanic Americans.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/asian-americans-p01] Most Asian Americans marry within their own ethnicities, but a significant number intermarry with other races.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/asian-americans-p01] Interracial Married couples in the United States in 2006: Asian men with Asian women was 2,493,000.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/asian-americans-p01] Asian men with White female married couples 174,000 while vice versa was 530,000.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/asian-americans-p01] Asian men with black women 6,000 compared to 34,000 vice versa.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/asian-americans-p01] Married couples in the United States in 2010: 2,885,000 Asian men with Asian females.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/asian-americans-p01] 219,000 Asian men with White females while vice versa was 529,000.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/asian-americans-p01] Asian men with Black women 9,000 while vice versa was 39,000.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/asian-americans-p01] According to a Pew Research Center survey conducted from July 5, 2022, to January 27, 2023, the religious landscape of Asian Americans is both diverse and evolving, encompassing Christianity, Buddhism, Hinduism, Islam, and the unaffiliated.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/asian-americans-p01] These religious identities often intersect with cultural practices, creating a unique blend of spirituality that varies significantly across subgroups.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/asian-americans-p01] Beyond formal identification, many Asian Americans express cultural or ancestral connections to religious traditions, highlighting the multifaceted role of religion in their lives.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/asian-americans-p01] Christianity has experienced the largest decline, dropping from 42% in 2012 to 34% in 2023, reflecting increasing secularisation in the United States and immigration from countries in which Christianity is a minority religion (China and India in particular).
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/asian-americans-p01] This development has been accompanied by a rise in traditional Asian religions, with the people identifying with them doubling during the same decade.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/asian-americans-p01] Christianity encompasses the largest tradition, accounting for 34% of Asian American adults.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/asian-americans-p01] This group is evenly split by Catholics (17%) and Protestants (16%), including 10% who identify as evangelical Protestants.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/asian-americans-p01] Beyond formal religious identification, an additional 18% report a cultural or familial closeness to Christianity.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/asian-americans-p01] Filipino and Korean Americans display particularly strong affiliations with Christianity.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/asian-americans-p01] Among Filipino Americans, 74% identify as Christian, and when considering those who feel culturally close to Christianity, this figure rises to 90%.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/asian-americans-p01] Among Korean Americans, 59% identify as Christians, and 81% express some connection to the faith.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/asian-americans-p01] Most Filipino Americans are Catholic (57%), whereas Korean Americans tend to be Protestant, with 34% identifying as evangelical Protestants.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/asian-americans-p01] The religiously unaffiliated encompasses individuals identifying as atheist, agnostic, or "nothing in particular." The share of those who are religiously unaffiliated has increased from 26% in 2012 to 32% in 2023.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/asian-americans-p01] Despite a lack of formal religious affiliation, a significant number of religiously unaffiliated Asian Americans maintain a connection to various religious or philosophical traditions due to cultural or ancestral reasons.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/asian-americans-p01] In total, only 12% of Asian Americans report having no connection to any religious or philosophical tradition.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/asian-americans-p01] Among Asian Americans, Chinese and Japanese Americans are more likely to be religiously unaffiliated, with 56% and 47% respectively identifying as such.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/asian-americans-p01] Both groups are also more likely to feel a cultural or ancestral connection to a faith tradition despite their lack of formal religious affiliation.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/asian-americans-p01] Conversely, Indian, Filipino, and Vietnamese Americans are considerably less likely to be religiously unaffiliated and more likely to express some form of connection to a religious tradition.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/asian-americans-p01] According to a 2023 Pew Research Center report, approximately 11% of Asian American adults identify as Buddhists, a slight decline from 14% in 2012.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/asian-americans-p01] Beyond formal identification, an additional 21% report feeling culturally or ancestrally connected to Buddhism, bringing the total with some affiliation to one-third of Asian Americans.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/asian-americans-p01] Among Vietnamese Americans, 37% identify as Buddhist - the highest proportion among major Asian American subgroups.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/asian-americans-p01] Among Japanese and Chinese Americans, formal Buddhist affiliation is less pronounced, but cultural connections remain robust.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/asian-americans-p01] For instance, while only 19% of Japanese Americans identify as Buddhist, a significant share feel a closeness to Buddhist traditions, reflecting its philosophical and cultural integration into their heritage.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/asian-americans-p01] Notably, home-based worship through shrines or altars is prevalent, with 63% of Asian American Buddhists practising such rituals compared to lower attendance rates at formal religious services.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/asian-americans-p01] About 11% of Asian American adults identify as Hindu, which has been stable since 2012.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/asian-americans-p01] Indian Americans constitute the largest group of Hindus, with nearly half (48%) identifying with this tradition.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/asian-americans-p01] Moreover, an additional 19% of Asian Americans report feeling a cultural or ancestral connection to Hinduism, reflecting the interplay between religious and cultural identities.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/asian-americans-p01] Altogether, two-thirds of Indian Americans express some form of affiliation with Hinduism, reflecting its central role within this community.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/asian-americans-p01] Hinduism among Asian Americans is notable for its private worship practices.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/asian-americans-p01] Nearly 79% of Asian American Hindus use an altar, shrine, or religious symbol for worship at home - the highest percentage among Asian American religious groups.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/asian-americans-p01] At the same time, 31% of Hindus also report attending religious services at least monthly.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/asian-americans-p01] Islam represents about 6% of Asian Americans, with an additional 3% expressing a cultural connection to the faith.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/asian-americans-p01] South Asian Americans, predominantly those of Pakistani and Bangladeshi origin, account for the largest share of Muslims followed by those of Indian origin.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/asian-americans-p01] For many Asian American Muslims, religion plays a central role in daily life.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/asian-americans-p01] About 60% report that religion is very important to them, and 54% attend mosque services at least monthly.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/asian-americans-p01] This group also emphasises communal practices, with a strong focus on maintaining religious traditions within family and community settings.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/asian-americans-p01] Because Asian Americans or their ancestors immigrated to the United States from many different countries, each Asian American population has its own unique immigration history.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/asian-americans-p01] Filipinos have been in the territories that would become the United States since the 16th century.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/asian-americans-p01] In 1635, an "East Indian" is listed in Jamestown, Virginia; preceding wider settlement of Indian immigrants on the East Coast in the 1790s and the West Coast in the 1800s.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/asian-americans-p01] In 1763, Filipinos established the small settlement of Saint Malo, Louisiana, after fleeing mistreatment aboard Spanish ships.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/asian-americans-p01] Since there were no Filipino women with them, these "Manilamen", as they were known, married Cajun and indigenous women.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/asian-americans-p01] Filipino farmworkers also played a major role in U.S. agriculture in the early 1900s.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/asian-americans-p01] They often faced poor working conditions and discrimination.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/asian-americans-p01] The first Japanese person to come to the United States, and stay any significant period of time was Nakahama Manjirō who reached the East Coast in 1841, and Joseph Heco became the first Japanese American naturalized US citizen in 1858.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/asian-americans-p01] Chinese sailors first came to Hawaii in 1789, a few years after Captain James Cook came upon the island.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/asian-americans-p01] Many settled and married Hawaiian women.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/asian-americans-p01] Most Chinese, Korean and Japanese immigrants in Hawaii or San Francisco arrived in the 19th century as laborers to work on sugar plantations or construction place.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/asian-americans-p01] There were thousands of Asians in Hawaii when it was annexed to the United States in 1898.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/asian-americans-p01] Later, Filipinos also came to work as laborers, attracted by the job opportunities, although they were limited.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/asian-americans-p01] Ryukyuans would start migrating to Hawaii in 1900.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/asian-americans-p01] Many Chinese immigrants played key roles in building the Transcontinental Railroad, but their stories were often left out of mainstream history.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/asian-americans-p01] According to a PBS article, "Descendants of Chinese Laborers Reclaim Railroad’s History," families today are working to recover and honor those forgotten histories.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/asian-americans-p01] Large-scale migration from Asia to the United States began when Chinese immigrants arrived on the West Coast in the mid-19th century.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/asian-americans-p01] Forming part of the California gold rush, these early Chinese immigrants participated intensively in the mining business and later in the construction of the transcontinental railroad.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/asian-americans-p01] By 1852, the number of Chinese immigrants in San Francisco had jumped to more than 20,000.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/asian-americans-p01] A wave of Japanese immigration to the United States began after the Meiji Restoration in 1868.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/asian-americans-p01] In 1898, all Filipinos in the Philippine Islands became American nationals when the United States took over colonial rule of the islands from Spain following the latter's defeat in the Spanish–American War.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/asian-americans-p01] The PBS documentary series Asian Americans highlights these stories and explores how Asian American communities have shaped the U.S. across centuries.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/asian-americans-p01] Under United States law during this period, particularly the Naturalization Act of 1790, only "free white persons" were eligible to naturalize as American citizens.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/asian-americans-p01] Ineligibility for citizenship prevented Asian immigrants from accessing a variety of rights, such as voting.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/asian-americans-p01] Bhicaji Balsara became the first known Indian-born person to gain naturalized US citizenship.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/asian-americans-p01] Balsara's naturalization was not the norm but an exception; in a pair of cases, *Ozawa v.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/asian-americans-p01] United States* (1922) and *United States v.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/asian-americans-p01] Bhagat Singh Thind* (1923), the Supreme Court upheld the racial qualification for citizenship and ruled that Asians were not "white persons".
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/asian-americans-p01] Second-generation Asian Americans, however, could become US citizens due to the birthright citizenship clause of the Fourteenth Amendment; this guarantee was confirmed as applying regardless of race or ancestry by the Supreme Court in *United States v.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/asian-americans-p01] From the 1880s to the 1920s, the United States passed laws inaugurating an era of exclusion of Asian immigrants.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/asian-americans-p01] Japanese immigration was sharply curtailed by a diplomatic agreement in 1907.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/asian-americans-p01] The Asiatic Barred Zone Act in 1917 further barred immigration from nearly all of Asia, the "Asiatic Zone".
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/asian-americans-p01] The Immigration Act of 1924 provided that no "alien ineligible for citizenship" could be admitted as an immigrant to the United States, consolidating the prohibition of Asian immigration.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/asian-americans-p01] President Roosevelt issued Executive Order 9066 on February 19, 1942, resulting in the internment of Japanese Americans, among others.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/asian-americans-p01] Over 100,000 people of Japanese descent, mostly on the West Coast, were forcibly removed, in an action later considered ineffective and racist.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/asian-americans-p01] Japanese Americans were kept isolated in military camps just because of their race, including children, old persons and the young generation.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/asian-americans-p01] World War II-era legislation and judicial rulings, such as the Magnuson Act of 1943 and Luce–Celler Act, gradually increased the ability of Asian Americans to immigrate and become naturalized citizens.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/asian-americans-p01] Immigration rapidly increased following the enactment of the Immigration and Nationality Act Amendments of 1965 as well as the influx of refugees from conflicts occurring in Southeast Asia such as the Vietnam War.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/asian-americans-p01] Asian American immigrants have a significant percentage of individuals who have already achieved professional status, a first among immigration groups.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/asian-americans-p01] The number of Asian immigrants to the United States "grew from 491,000 in 1960 to about 12.8 million in 2014, representing a 2,597 percent increase." Asian Americans were the fastest-growing racial group between 2000 and 2010.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/asian-americans-p01] By 2012, more immigrants came from Asia than from Latin America.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/asian-americans-p01] In 2015, Pew Research Center found that from 2010 to 2015 more immigrants came from Asia than from Latin America, and that since 1965; Asians have made up a quarter of all immigrants to the United States.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/asian-americans-p01] Asian immigrants "are more likely than the overall foreign-born population to be naturalized citizens"; in 2014, 59% of Asian immigrants had US citizenship, compared to 47% of all immigrants.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/asian-americans-p01] Prior to the 1960s, Asian immigrants and their descendants had organized and agitated for social or political purposes according to their particular ethnicity: Chinese, Japanese, Filipino, Korean, or Asian Indian.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/asian-americans-p01] The Asian American movement (a term coined by the Japanese American Yuji Ichioka and the Chinese American Emma Gee) gathered all those groups into a coalition, recognizing that they shared common problems with racial discrimination and common opposition to American imperialism, particularly in Asia.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/asian-americans-p01] The movement developed during the 1960s, inspired in part by the Civil Rights Movement and the protests against the Vietnam War.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/asian-americans-p01] "Drawing influences from the Black Power and antiwar movements, the Asian American movement forged a coalitional politics that united Asians of varying ethnicities and declared solidarity with other Third World people in the United States and abroad.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/asian-americans-p01] The movement as such was most active during the 1960s and 1970s.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/asian-americans-p01] Increasingly Asian American students demanded university-level research and teaching into Asian history and interaction with the United States.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/asian-americans-p01] They support multiculturalism and support affirmative action but oppose colleges' quota on Asian students viewed as discriminatory.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/asian-americans-p01] Asian Americans have been involved in the entertainment industry since the first half of the 19th century, when Chang and Eng Bunker (the original "Siamese Twins") became naturalized citizens.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/asian-americans-p01] Throughout the 20th century, acting roles in television, film, and theater were relatively few, and many available roles were for narrow, stereotypical characters.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/asian-americans-p01] Bruce Lee (born in San Francisco, CA) only achieved movie stardom after leaving the United States for Hong Kong.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/asian-americans-p01] More recently, young Asian American comedians and film-makers have found an outlet on YouTube allowing them to gain a strong and loyal fanbase among their fellow Asian Americans.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/asian-americans-p01] There have been several Asian American-centric television shows in American media, beginning with *Mr.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/asian-americans-p01] T and Tina* in 1976, and as recent as the TV series *Fresh Off the Boat* in 2015.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/asian-americans-p01] When Asian Americans were largely excluded from labor markets in the 19th century, they started their own businesses.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/asian-americans-p01] They have started convenience and grocery stores, professional offices such as medical and law practices, laundries, restaurants, beauty-related ventures, hi-tech companies, and many other kinds of enterprises, becoming very successful and influential in American society.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/asian-americans-p01] They have dramatically expanded their involvement across the American economy.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/asian-americans-p01] Asian Americans have been disproportionately successful in the hi-tech sectors of California's Silicon Valley, as evidenced by the Goldsea 100 Compilation of America's Most Successful Asian Entrepreneurs.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/asian-americans-p01] Compared to their population base, Asian Americans today are well represented in the professional sector and tend to earn higher wages.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/asian-americans-p01] The Goldsea compilation of Notable Asian American Professionals show that many have come to occupy high positions at leading US corporations, including a disproportionately large number as Chief Marketing Officers.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/asian-americans-p01] Asian Americans have made major contributions to the American economy.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/asian-americans-p01] In 2012, there were just under 486,000 Asian American-owned businesses in the US, which together employed more than 3.6 million workers, generating $707.6 billion in total receipts and sales, with annual payrolls of $112 billion.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/asian-americans-p01] In 2015, Asian American and Pacific Islander households had $455.6 billion in spending power (comparable to the annual revenue of Walmart) and made tax contributions of $184.0 billion.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/asian-americans-p01] Fashion designer and mogul Vera Wang, who is famous for designing dresses for high-profile celebrities, started a clothing company, named after herself, which now offers a broad range of luxury fashion products.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/asian-americans-p01] An Wang founded Wang Laboratories in June 1951.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/asian-americans-p01] Amar Bose founded the Bose Corporation in 1964.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/asian-americans-p01] Charles Wang founded Computer Associates, later became its CEO and chairman.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/asian-americans-p01] Two brothers, David Khym and Kenny Khym founded hip hop fashion giant Southpole in 1991.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/asian-americans-p01] Jen-Hsun "Jensen" Huang co-founded the Nvidia corporation in 1993.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/asian-americans-p01] Andrea Jung serves as chairman and CEO of Avon Products.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/asian-americans-p01] Vinod Khosla was a founding CEO of Sun Microsystems and is a general partner of the prominent venture capital firm Kleiner Perkins Caufield & Byers.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/asian-americans-p01] Steve Chen and Jawed Karim were co-creators of YouTube, and were beneficiaries of Google's $1.65 billion acquisition of that company in 2006.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/asian-americans-p01] Eric Yuan, founder of Zoom Video Communications, and Shahid Khan, owner of the Jacksonville Jaguars among others, are both in the US top 100 in terms of net worth, according to Forbes.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/asian-americans-p01] In addition to contributing greatly to other fields, Asian Americans have made considerable contributions in science and technology in the United States, in such prominent innovative R&D regions as Silicon Valley and The Triangle.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/asian-americans-p01] Asian Americans have a high level of political incorporation in terms of their actual voting population.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/asian-americans-p01] Since 1907, Asian Americans have been active at the national level and have had multiple officeholders at local, state, and national levels.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/asian-americans-p01] As more Asian Americans have been elected to public office, they have had a growing impact on foreign relations of the United States, immigration, international trade, and other topics.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/asian-americans-p01] The first Asian American to be elected to the United States Congress was Dalip Singh Saund in 1957.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/asian-americans-p01] The highest ranked Asian American to serve in the United States Congress was Senator and President pro tempore Daniel Inouye, who died in office in 2012.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/asian-americans-p01] There are several active Asian Americans in the United States Congress.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/asian-americans-p01] With higher proportions and densities of Asian American populations, Hawaii has most consistently sent Asian Americans to the Senate, and Hawaii and California have most consistently sent Asian Americans to the House of Representatives.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/asian-americans-p01] The first Asian American member of the US cabinet was Norman Mineta, who served as Secretary of Commerce and then Secretary of Transportation in the George W.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/asian-americans-p01] As of 2021, the highest ranked Asian American by order of precedence is Vice President Kamala Harris.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/asian-americans-p01] Previously, the highest ranked Asian American was Secretary of Transportation Elaine Chao (2017–2021), who had also been in the order of precedence as US Secretary of Labor (2001–2009).
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/asian-americans-p01] There have been roughly "about a half-dozen viable Asian-American candidates" to ever run for president of the United States.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/asian-americans-p01] Senator Hiram Fong of Hawaii, the child of Chinese immigrants, was a "favorite son" candidate at the Republican National Conventions of 1964 and 1968.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/asian-americans-p01] Mink of Hawaii, a Japanese American, unsuccessfully sought the Democratic nomination for president.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/asian-americans-p01] Louisiana Governor Bobby Jindal, the son of Indian immigrants, unsuccessfully sought the Republican nomination for president in 2016.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/asian-americans-p01] Entrepreneur and nonprofit founder Andrew Yang, the son of Taiwanese immigrants, unsuccessfully sought the Democratic nomination for president in 2020.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/asian-americans-p01] In January 2021, Kamala Harris, the daughter of an Indian mother and a Jamaican father became the first Asian American Vice President of the United States.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/asian-americans-p01] King Bhumibol Adulyadej (1927–2016) was the first monarch to be born in the United States.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/asian-americans-p01] He reigned the throne of Thailand from 1946 to 2016.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/asian-americans-p01] Connie Chung was one of the first Asian American national correspondents for a major TV news network, reporting for CBS in 1971.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/asian-americans-p01] She later co-anchored the *CBS Evening News* from 1993 to 1995, becoming the first Asian American national news anchor.
[src:adams-run-south-carolina/asian-americans-p01] At ABC, Ken Kashiwahara began reporting nationally in 1974.
